{"title_page": "Poppy (entertainer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer and YouTube personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Poppy\n| image              = Poppy - 2016 (portrait).jpg\n| caption            = Poppy in 2016\n| birth_name         = Moriah Rose Pereira\n| birth_date         = <!--Please don't remove the birthday anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but matter is that she was born on January 1, 1995. Professional biographer Neil Z. Yeung of Apple Music has even attributed her birth to this date.-->{{Birth date and age|1995|01|01}}\n| birth_place        = <!--Please don't remove the birthplace anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but the fact of the matter is that she was born near Boston.-->{{nowrap|near [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pandell|first=Lexi|title=Welcome to Poppy's World|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|journal=Wired|accessdate=February 15, 2018|date=June 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Singer, [[YouTuber]]\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| website            = {{URL|impoppy.com}}\n| signature          = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| alias              = {{flatlist|\n* That Poppy\n* Poppy Chan\n* {{nowrap|Moriah Poppy}}\n}}\n| instrument         = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n* synthesizer\n* electronic organ\n}}\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Electropop]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[art pop]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[nu metal]]\n* [[kawaii metal]]<ref>{{cite web \n|last1=PASBANI |first1=ROBERT |title=IRONBUNNY Is The Japanese Metal Group with A Cyborg Guitarist You've Been Waiting For |url=https://metalinjection.net/av/new-music/ironbunny-is-the-japanese-metal-group-with-a-cyborg-guitarist-youve-been-waiting-for |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n* I'm Poppy\n* {{nowrap|[[Mad Decent]]}}\n* [[Sumerian Records|Sumerian]]\n}}\n| associated_acts               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Diplo]]\n* [[Fever 333]]\n* [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| channel_name     = thatPoppyTV\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* Entertainment\n* [[internet culture]]\n* satire\n* pop culture\n* music\n}}\n| silver_button    = yes\n| silver_year      = 2016\n| gold_button      = yes\n| gold_year        = 2017\n| subscribers      = 2.58 million\n| subscriber_date  = September 10, 2019\n| views            = 478+ million\n| view_date        = February 3, 2020\n| ages             =\n| stats_update     = \n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Moriah Rose Pereira''' (born January 1, 1995),<ref>{{cite news|title=Poppy is a disturbing internet meme seen by millions. Can she become a pop sensation?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|newspaper=The Guardian|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127205557/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|archivedate=January 27, 2018|date=December 11, 2017|last1=Hunt|first1=Elle}}</ref> known professionally as '''Poppy''', is an American singer, songwriter, [[YouTuber]], and religious leader.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/poppy-youtube-religion-2017-11|title=Meet Poppy, the 22-year-old YouTube star who has already inspired her own religion|first=Zo\u00eb|last=Bernard|website=Business Insider}}</ref><ref name=auto/> In 2013, Poppy moved to [[Los Angeles]] where she rose to prominence while working with director and musician [[Titanic Sinclair]] who helped her enhance her YouTube presence by making short performance art videos and music videos. In 2015, she signed a recording contract with [[Island Records]], subsequently releasing her debut extended play, ''[[Bubblebath (EP)|Bubblebath]]'', as '''That Poppy'''.\n\nIn late 2016, Poppy became the face of [[Sanrio]]'s \"Hello Sanrio\" collection.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|title=Welcome to Poppy's World|last=Pandell|first=Lexi|work=WIRED|access-date=October 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020005326/https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|archivedate=October 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In the summer of 2017, she signed to [[Mad Decent]], and in October released her first studio album, ''[[Poppy.Computer]]''. To promote the album she embarked on [[Poppy.Computer Tour|her first tour]], which consisted of 34 North American cities separated by shows in London and Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/slideshows/poppy-at-slims-oct-27-2017/|title=Poppy at Slim's Oct. 26, 2017 \u2013 By geoffrey-smith-ii \u2013 October 30, 2017 \u2013 SF Weekly|date=October 30, 2017|work=SF Weekly|access-date=November 12, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112185300/http://www.sfweekly.com/slideshows/poppy-at-slims-oct-27-2017/|archivedate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, she released her [[web television]] series, ''[[I'm Poppy]]'', and her second studio album, ''[[Am I a Girl?]].'' On January 10, 2020, [[Sumerian Records]] published her third studio album, ''[[I Disagree]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/poppy-concrete-sumerian-records/|title=Poppy debuts new track \"Concrete,\" signs with Sumerian Records|last=Shoemaker|first=Whitney|date=August 22, 2019|website=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|altpress.com]]|language=English|quote=After dropping teasers throughout the week, Poppy has unveiled her latest track 'Concrete' and announced her signing to Sumerian Records.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/poppy_goes_metal_with_new_album_i_disagree|title=Poppy Goes Metal with New Album 'I Disagree|last=Thiessen|first=Brock|date=October 4, 2019|website=[[Exclaim!|exclaim.ca]]|language=English|quote=The album is due out on January 10 via Sumerian Records, and it promises to be quite the departure for Poppy.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMoriah Rose Pereira was born near [[Boston]], Massachusetts<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|title=Poppy is a disturbing internet meme seen by millions. Can she become a pop sensation?|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127205557/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|archivedate=January 27, 2018}}</ref><!--Please don't remove the birthday anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but the fact of the matter is that she was born on January 1, 1995. Professional biographer Neil Z. Yeung of [[Apple Music]] has even attributed her birth to this date.--> on January 1, 1995. She grew up in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> She recalls wanting to be a [[The Rockettes|Rockette]] as a child and grew up dancing,<ref name=\"amp\">{{cite web |url=http://923amp.cbslocal.com/2016/03/01/that-poppy-talks-princesses-unicorns-and-real-life-experiences-with-niko/ |title=That Poppy Talks 'Princesses, Unicorns, and Real Life Experiences' with Niko |author=Niko |date=March 1, 2016 |website=92.3 AMP Radio |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816111853/http://923amp.cbslocal.com/2016/03/01/that-poppy-talks-princesses-unicorns-and-real-life-experiences-with-niko/ |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 14, 2017  }}</ref> which she did for 11 years.<ref name=\"jakestake\">{{cite web|url=http://jakes-take.com/2015/07/the-five-question-challenge-with-that-poppy/ |title=The Five Question Challenge with That Poppy |date=July 7, 2015 |website=Jake's Take |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817041002/http://jakes-take.com/2015/07/the-five-question-challenge-with-that-poppy/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Elyachar |first=Jacob |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref> She is naturally a brunette.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.wetheunicorns.com/features/age-real-name-height-moriah-pereira-instagram/|title=Who Is Poppy? Everything You Need To Know About The Mysterious YouTuber|website=amp.wetheunicorns.com|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 18, Poppy left home for Los Angeles in pursuit of an entertainment career.\n\n==Career==\n===2012\u20132014: Early performances===\nPrior to 2014, Poppy performed at [[social media]] festivals, including [[VidCon]] in June 2012 and [[DigiTour Media|DigiTour]] in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2013/06/poppy-and-sam-pepper-interview |title=YouTube Stars Poppy & Sam Pepper Chat New Music, Translate Phrase \"Turnt Up\" |date=June 11, 2013 |website=Fuse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305200004/http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2013/06/poppy-and-sam-pepper-interview |archive-date=March 5, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> Poppy began her musical career by singing cover songs on the internet.\n\n===2015\u20132016: YouTube partnership with Titanic Sinclair, ''Bubblebath'', ''3:36 (Music to Sleep To)''===\nPoppy moved to Los Angeles in 2013 to pursue her musical career.<ref name=\"racked\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |title=Parsing the Aesthetics of That Poppy, Pop Singer and Internet Enigma |date=April 11, 2016 |website=Racked |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718003313/http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |archive-date=July 18, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Brooke |first=Eliza |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref> There she teamed up with former [[Music video director|director]] Corey Michael Mixter,<ref>{{cite web|title=Corey Michael Mixter|url=https://genius.com/artists/corey-michael-mixter|website=Genius|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021105/https://genius.com/artists/Corey-michael-mixter|archivedate=October 7, 2017}}</ref> best known by his stage name [[Titanic Sinclair]], to make a series of abstract promotional videos on a YouTube channel originally titled \"thatPoppyTV\". The channel is now simply known as \"Poppy\". As of April 2018, the channel is actively uploading videos and has attracted a large audience. In 2015, she signed to [[Island Records]] under the name That Poppy and released her debut song, \"Everybody Wants to Be Poppy\", in June of that year.<ref name=\"island Records\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islandrecords.com/news/that-poppy-releases-everybody-wants-to-be-poppy/ |title=That Poppy Releases 'Everybody Wants to Be Poppy' |date=June 23, 2015 |website=Island Records |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105004141/http://www.islandrecords.com/news/that-poppy-releases-everybody-wants-to-be-poppy/ |archive-date=November 5, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She performed at the Corona Capital Festival in November 2015.<ref name=\"tono\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tono.tv/fotos-poppy-en-el-corona-capital-2015/ |title=Fotos: Poppy en el Corona Capital 2015 |date=November 24, 2015 |website=TONO |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308150224/http://www.tono.tv/fotos-poppy-en-el-corona-capital-2015/ |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |last=Fran\u00e7ois |first=Toni |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"axscc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.axs.com/corona-capital-announce-their-2015-festival-lineup-56098 |title=Corona Capital announce their 2015 festival lineup |date=June 1, 2015 |website=AXS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308143217/http://www.axs.com/corona-capital-announce-their-2015-festival-lineup-56098 |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |last=Lopez |first=Ashleyan |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She released the song, \"[[Lowlife (Poppy song)|Lowlife]]\", a month after releasing her first single \"Everybody Wants to Be Poppy\" and released her first EP, a four-track pop record called ''[[Bubblebath (EP)|Bubblebath]]'', on [[Island Records|Island]] in February 2016.<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{Citation|last=That Poppy|title=Bubblebath|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Bubblebath-Explicit-That-Poppy/dp/B01BKTUG9O/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&qid=1466978210&sr=8-2&keywords=that+poppy&linkCode=ll1&linkId=185874ad00b207a936478b6c14c683ac |accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.circa.com/story/2017/07/18/hollywood/youtube-star-that-poppy-talks-career-live|title=YouTube sensation That Poppy gave us the most wonderfully bizarre interview ever about her life and career|access-date=July 19, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728090019/https://www.circa.com/story/2017/07/18/hollywood/youtube-star-that-poppy-talks-career-live|archivedate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> The EP consists of four songs; [[Lowlife (song)|\"Lowlife]]\", \"Money\", \"Altar\", and \"American Kids\". In August 2016, she released a series of advertisements for the shoe company [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]] on her channel as a part of its ''Steve Madden Music'' program.<ref name=\"stevemaddensite\">{{cite web |author=Steve Madden |title=That Poppy: STEVE MADDEN |url=http://www.stevemadden.com/content.jsp?pageName=ThatPoppy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816184347/http://www.stevemadden.com/content.jsp?pageName=ThatPoppy |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |website=Steve Madden |accessdate=May 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, Poppy released an [[Experimental music|experimental]] [[ambient music]] album called ''[[3:36 (Music to Sleep To)]]'', composed by Titanic Sinclair and herself, with assistance from [[Polysomnography|polysomnographists]] from the [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] [[Washington University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impoppy.bandcamp.com/album/3-36-music-to-sleep-to |title=3:36 (Music To Sleep To) |website=Bandcamp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308133746/https://impoppy.bandcamp.com/album/3-36-music-to-sleep-to |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, she became the face of Japanese retailer [[Sanrio]]'s first \"Hello Sanrio\" collection.\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Poppy.Computer'', Poppy.Church, Mars Argo lawsuit, and ''Am I a Girl?''===\n[[File:Poppy Tour.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy performing live at YouTube Space in Los Angeles]]\n[[File:That Poppy.jpg|thumb|During the ''Poppy.Computer'' Tour, October 2017]]\nIn February 2017, Poppy starred in a series of videos for [[Comedy Central]] called \"Internet Famous with Poppy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s7JnLRwAdAI|title=Internet Famous with Poppy \u2013 Brandon Wardell|date=February 13, 2017|via=YouTube|publisher=Comedy Central|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> That September, she won a Streamy award in the category 'Breakthrough Artist'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abrams Artists Agency Signs Viral Musician Poppy |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/11/26/abrams-artists-agency-signs-viral-musician-poppy-youtube-tour/ |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |work=Tubefilter |date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Poppy 10 31 2018 -28 (46548657641).jpg|thumb|Poppy performing live at The Wiltern in Los Angeles, California, on Wednesday, October 31, 2018]]\n\nPoppy's debut studio album, ''[[Poppy.Computer]]'', was released on October 6, 2017 by [[Mad Decent]]. Her first concert tour, the 36-city [[Poppy.Computer Tour|''Poppy.Computer'' Tour]], started on October 19 in [[Vancouver]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} In November, Poppy announced that her second studio album was \"almost ready\", and that she was going to Japan again to finish it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://1033ampradio.radio.com/2017/11/22/poppy-is-almost-done-with-second-album-more-tour-dates-coming/ |title=Poppy's interview for 103.3 AMP |website=103.3 AMP |accessdate=November 22, 2017 |date=November 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033335/http://1033ampradio.radio.com/2017/11/22/poppy-is-almost-done-with-second-album-more-tour-dates-coming/ |archivedate=December 1, 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPoppy made her ''[[YouTube Rewind]]'' debut in 2017, and was one of the few content creators to get their own lines.\n\nIn March 2018, Poppy performed at the Japanese pop music festival, Popspring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popspring.jp/2018/poppy.html |title=Poppy Popspring |website=Popspring.jp |accessdate=April 7, 2018 |date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2018, Sinclair's former partner [[Mars Argo]] filed a 44-page lawsuit in [[United States District Court for the Central District of California|Central California court]] against Sinclair and Poppy alleging copyright infringement, stating that Sinclair based Poppy's online persona on hers, as well as emotional and physical abuse Sinclair had allegedly subjected to her in the period after their separation and the subsequent abandonment of the project.<ref name=\"tmzlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=YouTube Feud: Mars Sues Titanic and ThatPoppy: You Jacked My Identity!!!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/17/youtube-legal-feud-titanic-sinclair-mars-argo-thatpoppy/|publisher=[[TMZ]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> On May 7, Poppy made a public statement about the \"frivolous\" lawsuit, saying Argo was attempting to manipulate her psychologically. She called the suit a \"publicity campaign\" and a \"desperate grab for fame\".<ref name=\"billboardlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Poppy Responds to Mars Argo Copyright Suit, Calls It 'Desperate Grab for Fame'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8454780/poppy-responds-mars-argo-copyright-lawsuit-desperate-grab-for-fame/|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref> The Sinclair case was settled out of court on September 14 \"with no money exchanging hands\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/poppy-and-manager-titanic-sinclair-settle-lawsuit-with-mars-argo-2428225|title=Poppy and collaborator Titanic Sinclair settle lawsuit with Mars Argo|work=NME|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/lawsuit-poppy-titanic-sinclair-dismissed/|title=Lawsuit against YouTube personality Poppy dismissed|date=September 18, 2018|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Argo released a statement in January 2019 that all rights to Mars Argo had been assigned to her as part of the settlement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/marsargo/status/1083047047966539776|title=pic.twitter.com/4P670nKPuj|first=Mars|last=Argo|date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The copyright case against Poppy was dismissed.\n[[File:Poppy 10 31 2018 -2 (45635254575).jpg|thumb|left|Poppy performing at [[Pellissier Building and Wiltern Theatre|The Wiltern]] during her [[Am I a Girl? Tour|''Am I a Girl?'' Tour]]]]\nOn July 6, 2018, Poppy released a cover of [[Gary Numan]]'s song \"[[Metal (song)|Metal]]\" as a single on all digital platforms.<ref name=\"iTunesMetal\">{{cite web|title=iTunes Metal|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/metal-single/1405863089|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref> On July 27, she released the first single for the album ''[[Am I a Girl?]]'' titled \"In a Minute\".<ref name=\"iTunesInAMinute\">{{cite web|title=iTunes in a Minute \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-a-minute-single/1416243366|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=July 27, 2018}}</ref> She released the album's second single \"[[Time Is Up (song)|Time Is Up]]\", which features American DJ [[Diplo]], on August 22.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes Time Is Up \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/time-is-up-feat-diplo-single/1425178835|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/poppy-and-diplo-team-up-for-new-song-time-is-up-listen/amp/|title=Poppy and Diplo Team Up for New Song 'Time Is Up': Listen |website=Pitchfork|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/dance/8471646/poppy-diplo-time-is-up|title=Poppy and Diplo Celebrate the Robot Takeover On 'Time Is Up': Watch|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref> she released \"Fashion After All\" on October 12.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fashion After All|date=October 12, 2018|url=https://open.spotify.com/track/1fG2o4l6jDPDJPdWIMoG3u?si=bunvY-NfQFaYW1zMfh7Xgg|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Fashion After All by Poppy|date=October 12, 2018|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/fashion-after-all/1438151959?i=1438151960|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> \"Hard Feelings\" was released on October 19 and \"X\" was released on October 25.  In September 2018, Poppy announced on her social media that she was already working on her third studio album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1042407821835468802|title=Poppy's Twitter September 19th, 2018 |website=Twitter |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |date=September 19, 2018 }}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref> On September 11, Poppy's Twitter account announced an album release and costume party for October 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1039645459009204224|title=Poppy's Twitter September 11th, 2018 |website=Twitter |accessdate=October 8, 2018 |date=September 11, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Poppy began to drop hints about a new project and website called Poppy.Church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://poppy.church/|title=Poppy.Church|website=poppy.church|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> At first, the purpose of the website was not known, as it only featured a cryptic message and an opportunity to enter one's phone number. After a few months, however, the purpose of the site was made clear. Every day at 3:36 PDT, certain people who entered their phone number would receive a link to join the Church. There they could fill out a profile, create an avatar, and pledge their allegiance to her. As of August 24, there is an Atrium, which acts as a chatroom, a theater, a gallery which changes weekly, a lobby like another chatroom, a bulletin board with announcements, a personal report page, a box office selling tickets for Poppy's ''Am I a Girl?'' tour,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poppy.church/box-office|title=Box Office|website=poppy.church|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> a backpack, and a settings page to edit contact information and character. On August 23, room invites were sent out to members of the Church who were showing \"Faith, Dedication, and Loyalty\". There are 100,000 rooms, with 1,000 halls connecting to the corresponding 100 rooms in that hall. (For example, Hall No. 1 has rooms 1\u2013100, Hall No. 2 has rooms 101\u2013200, and so on.) Members of the Church can visit each other's rooms, leave comments on their walls, and access provided social media.\n\nPoppy attended the [[American Music Awards of 2018|2018 American Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/poppy-black-mask-2018-american-music-awards/amp|title=Poppy Wore a Black Latex Mask to the 2018 American Music Awards|website=wmagazine.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/poppy/ama-outfit-mask/|title=People Are LOSING IT Over What Poppy Wore to the AMAs|website=amp.wetheunicorns.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/american-music-awards-2018-worst-13392860.amp|title=American Music Awards 2018 \u2013 The Worst Dressed|date=October 10, 2018|work=mirror|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> After winning the Breakthrough Artist in 2017, Poppy returned to the [[Streamy Awards]] in 2018 as a presenter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/10/23/youtuber-poppy-walks-the-streamys-red-carpet-with-three-dates-in-gimp-suits-8066620/|title=YouTuber Poppy walks the Streamys red carpet with three dates in gimp suits|date=October 23, 2018|work=Metro|access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/poppy/streamys-gimps-outfit/|title=You won't believe what Poppy took to the Streamy Awards...|work=We The Unicorns|access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Genesis 1'', ''A Jester's Tale'', ''Choke'' and ''I Disagree''===\n\nOn January 8, 2019, Poppy announced a graphic novel through Z2 Comics entitled ''Genesis 1'', which was released to comic book stores on July 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/poppy-moves-comics-genesis-1-graphic-novel-1174634|title=Musician Poppy Moves to Comics for 'Genesis 1' Graphic Novel|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The graphic novel tells the origin of Poppy. The description on Z2 Comics' website reads \"Is she a girl? Is she a machine? Is she humanity's redemption, or its damnation? Don't be scared \u2013 either way, she is Poppy\u2026 and you love Poppy. Witness the genesis of the internet phenomenon in this original graphic novel, bundled with an exclusive brand new album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comiccrusaders.com/poppy-announces-first-ever-graphic-novel-genesis-1-available-july-2019/|title=POPPY ANNOUNCES FIRST EVER GRAPHIC NOVEL 'GENESIS 1' AVAILABLE JULY 2019 \u2013 Comic Crusaders|first=Al|last=Mega|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> It was co-written by Poppy, Titanic Sinclair and Ryan Cady, with art by Masa Minoura and Ian McGinty. She elaborated in an interview with Gigwise that the album released with the graphic novel, titled ''I C U: Music to Read To'', is an ambient music album meant to be listened to while reading.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gigwise.com/features/3304522/poppy-interview-new-coming-book-release-and-companion-album|title=Poppy talks new ambient release, being a religious leader, + embracing heavy metal|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' announced Poppy would star in the [[augmented-reality]] experience ''A Jester's Tale'' created and directed by Asad J. Malik. It was produced by [[RYOT]] and 1RIC, premiering at the Sundance Film Festival as part of the New Frontier program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8494669/poppy-a-jesters-tale-ar-experience-sundance-2019|title=Poppy to Star in Augmented Reality Experience 'A Jester's Tale,' Premiering at Sundance 2019: Exclusive|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> The storyline \"transports viewers inside a child's bedroom to meet a cast of character holograms\". Later that month in an interview to ''[[Forbes]]'', Poppy announced her new single and video called \"Voicemail\", produced and directed by Titanic Sinclair. It was released on January 31.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/01/25/poppy-voicemail-new-single-sundance-2019-interview/|title=Poppy Shares Details on New Single 'Voicemail,' WWE Collaboration, AR Experience at Sundance & More|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> After attending the [[IHeartRadio Music Awards|iHeartRadio awards]] in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehollywoodgossip.com/gallery/that-poppy-2016-iheartradio-music-awards/|title=That Poppy: 2016 iHeartRadio Music Awards|last=Lynch|first=Kelly|date=April 4, 2016|website=The Hollywood Gossip|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> she returned in 2019 wearing a dress designed by [[Viktor & Rolf]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stealherstyle.net/2019/03/15/poppy-2019-iheartradio-music-awards/|title=Poppy: 2019 iHeartRadio Music Awards|date=March 15, 2019|website=Steal Her Style|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/poppy-viktor-and-rolf-couture-iheartradio-awards|title=Poppy Wears Viktor and Rolf's 2019 Couture to the iHeartRadio Music Awards 2019|last=Okwodu|first=Janelle|website=Vogue|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> and sat front row at their fashion show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/poppy-iheart-radio-viktor-rolf-meme-dress|title=Poppy Shows Up at iHeartRadio Music Awards in Fashion Week's Most Memed Dress|last=Eckardt|first=Stephanie|website=wmagazine.com|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/singer-poppy-attends-the-victor-rolf-haute-couture-fall-news-photo/1159864098|title=Singer Poppy attends the Victor&Rolf Haute Couture Fall/Winter 2019...|website=Getty Images|language=en-us|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Poppy revealed plans for a movie and her own [[music streaming]] service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stockx.com/news/thats-five-with-poppy/|title=That's Five with Poppy|date=March 15, 2019|website=StockX News|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> She attended the ''Billboard'' Music Awards. Her song \"Scary Mask\" was released on May 29, and featured American rock band [[Fever 333]]. The song was included on her second EP, ''Choke'', which was on released on June 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5d001aa3b8bad3671fd7bfc5/|title=Poppy Is The Face of Nu-Metal in 2019 {{!}} BUILD Series NYC|website=Build Series|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, Poppy announced that her third studio album entitled ''[[I Disagree]]'' would be released on January 10, 2020 through [[Sumerian Records]]. The title track was released as the second single from the album (following \"[[Concrete (Poppy song)|Concrete]]\" in August) on October 4 alongside the album pre-order. The album continues the [[Heavy metal music|metal]] sound featured on her 2019 EP ''Choke'' and the latter half of ''Am I a Girl?''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wallofsoundau.com/2019/10/04/poppy-announces-new-album-i-disagree-unleashed-the-title-track-single/|title=Poppy Announces New Album \"I Disagree\" + Unleashed The Title Track Single|date=October 4, 2019|website=Wall Of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> \"[[Bloodmoney]]\" was released as the third single from the album on November 6, 2019, and \"Fill The Crown\" was released as the fourth single from the album on December 11, 2019. The final single from the album, \"Anything Like Me,\" was released alongside the album and the music video for the track on 10 January 2020. \n\nOn December 28, Poppy released a statement confirming that she and Sinclair parted ways. She accused him of glamorizing suicide and using this to manipulate her, alleging she and Sinclair's former collaborator Mars Argo suffered similar psychological abuse.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/poppy-titanic-sinclair-accuses-manipulative-patterns-2591556|title=Poppy parts ways with Titanic Sinclair, accuses him of \"manipulative patterns\"|last=Lavin|first=Will|work=NME|date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Poppy announced her second graphic novel, titled ''Damnation: Poppy's Inferno''. It will be published on July 21, 2020 alongside a soundtrack album, ''Music to Scream To''.\n\n==YouTube==\nPoppy's YouTube channel was created on October 6, 2011, and her earliest video is from November 2014, an abstract skit called ''Poppy Eats Cotton Candy'', directed by Titanic Sinclair. The videos are described by their producer Sinclair as \"a combination of [[Andy Warhol]]'s pop accessibility, [[David Lynch]]'s creepiness, and [[Tim Burton]]'s zany comedic tone\".<ref name=\"racked\" /> The channel has been discussed by other YouTubers, including [[PewDiePie]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vdGiqRjTd34 |title=I'M POPPY! |last=PewDiePie |date=December 3, 2016 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223113628/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vdGiqRjTd34 |archive-date=December 23, 2016 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017}}</ref> [[Social Repose]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Social Repose|title=Goth Reacts to Poppy|date=October 14, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XJg9uzbXoCk|accessdate=May 22, 2017}}</ref> Night Mind,<ref>{{Citation|last=Night Mind|title=Who Is Poppy?|date=July 7, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NmXQKMjEC8E|accessdate=July 18, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822074146/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NmXQKMjEC8E|archivedate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> the [[MatPat|Film Theorists]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CqdE2EKhJG4 |title=Poppy's Hidden Conspiracy EXPOSED! |date=January 24, 2017 |website= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312044551/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CqdE2EKhJG4 |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017 |author=The Film Theorists}}</ref> Reaction Time, and the [[Fine Brothers]] on their ''[[React (media franchise)|React]]'' series. She starred in an episode in which she reacts to children reacting to her videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xqH3KaW25AA |title=Poppy Reacts to Kids React to Poppy |date=February 22, 2017 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307102916/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xqH3KaW25AA |archive-date=March 7, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017 |author=[[The Fine Brothers]]}}</ref> She has also appeared in an episode of the acclaimed web series ''[[Good Mythical Morning]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kls6wSVqbrY|title=Will It Poppy?|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nSinclair alludes in an interview that Poppy's character in the promotional videos presented itself to him as an [[Android (robot)|android]] and how some of the concept relates to the [[uncanny valley]] hypothesis.<ref name=\"Dom\">{{Citation|last=Dom's Sketch Cast|title=Titanic Sinclair {{!}} DSC Interview|date=October 31, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l81ienfgzss|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref> Poppy has stated that her YouTube videos tell a story.<ref>{{Citation|last=NME|title=Poppy on 'Am I A Girl', Grimes, Marilyn Manson and the future|date=October 26, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYqyAHfRatM|access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAside from her abstract promotional videos, Poppy's channel features her original music,<ref>{{Citation|last=Poppy |title=Poppy \u2013 Computer Boy (Official Video) |date=May 19, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Ao5mg11xIk |accessdate=May 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519171542/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Ao5mg11xIk&gl=US&hl=en |archivedate=May 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://popcrush.com/poppy-lets-make-a-video-watch/|title=Poppy Makes a Video For 'Let's Make a Video'|website=PopCrush|access-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711204401/http://popcrush.com/poppy-lets-make-a-video-watch/|archivedate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> various covers, and [[acoustic music|acoustic]] versions of her songs.\n\nPoppy's friend Charlotte, a celebrity-interviewing [[mannequin]] with a [[Speech synthesis|synthetic voice]], is a recurring character. She usually appears interacting with Poppy but also on her own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/poppy-youtube-cult/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901112147/https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/poppy-youtube-cult/|url-status=dead|title=The Cult Appeal of Poppy, the Perfect Pop Idol of the Future|date=August 16, 2017|archivedate=September 1, 2017|website=The Daily Dot}}</ref> She appears to have developed a drug and jealousy problem after Poppy became famous, which strains their relationship,<ref name=wired>{{cite journal | url = https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/ | title = Welcome to Poppy's World | date = June 4, 2017 | accessdate = June 5, 2017 | journal = Wired | author = Lexi Pandell | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170604213635/https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/ | archivedate = June 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDJjDZ_PuPY&list=PLqt12vbt3qkcCPIX-NjyftjMtIea1b5nA|title=Poppy is Over|last=Poppy|date=April 12, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> although Charlotte became Poppy's opening act for her 2017\u20132018 [[Poppy.Computer Tour|''Poppy.Computer'' Tour]]. Other characters include Charlotte's son, a boy mannequin who has taken the brunt of abuse at the hands of his mother during a drugged stupor; Plant (voiced by Sinclair), a potted basil plant who is one of Poppy's closest friends and biggest supporter; and Skeleton (also voiced by Sinclair), a plastic model skeleton who is revealed as Charlotte's drug dealer.\n\nThe channel also has an animated promotional [[miniseries]] called ''Everybody Wants to Be Poppy'', directed by Titanic Sinclair and illustrated by Melanie Foreman, which stars Poppy as herself, Titanic Sinclair as Rex, actor [[Matt Bennett]] as Pho, Canadian singer-songwriter [[Simon Wilcox]] as Phoebe, and Los Angeles-based photographer Sam McGuire as Wyatt. The series documents Poppy and Rex's journey as they attempt to find a \"magical [[kale]] [[smoothie]]\".<ref name=\"animated\">{{cite web|title='Everybody Wants to be Poppy' Episode: 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-PTVaWj-yuE|via=YouTube|date=June 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''I'm Poppy'' series==\n{{Main|I'm Poppy}}\n''[[I'm Poppy]]'', a short film and the first episode of a television series of the same name written and directed by Titanic Sinclair, made its world premiere on January 23 at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]]. In it, Poppy leaves the Internet for the real world and confronts the pitfalls of fame, including cults, deranged fans, Satan, and her bitter rival Charlotte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/2018-festival-shorts-indie-episodic-special-events|title=SUNDANCE INSTITUTE ANNOUNCES INDIE EPISODIC, SHORTS & SPECIAL EVENT SELECTIONS FOR 2018 SUNDANCE FILM FESTIVAL|website=sundance.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Poppy\" Will Be the Weirdest Thing Ever on YouTube Red|url= https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/im-poppy-youtube-red-release-date-trailer-1202669317 |work= Variety |accessdate=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180124071013/http://variety.com/2018/digital/news/im-poppy-youtube-red-release-date-trailer-1202669317/|archivedate=January 24, 2018|date= January 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nPoppy explains that her stage name originated as a nickname a friend used to call her. After her friend persistently introduced her as \"Poppy\", the name stuck.<ref>{{cite web|title=#GIRLTALK: Official interview with singer That POPPY|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_8XSVlDkhPQ|via=YouTube|accessdate=October 11, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723172012/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_8XSVlDkhPQ|archivedate=July 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPoppy has described herself as a \"[[kawaii]] [[Barbie]] child\".<ref name=\"next2shine\" /><ref name=\"ladygunn\">{{cite web|url=http://ladygunn.com/music/sugar-and-spice-a-cute-chat-with-that-poppy |title=Suggar and Spice: A Cute Chat With That Poppy! |date=October 22, 2015 |website=Ladygunn |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028145807/http://ladygunn.com/music/sugar-and-spice-a-cute-chat-with-that-poppy |archive-date=October 28, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Hardy |first=Alyssa |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She has described her music style as \"music [that] makes you want to rule the world.\" Poppy states that she drew inspiration from genres such as [[J-pop]] and [[K-pop]], as well as [[reggae]]. She recalls beginning to write music in 2012. She told ''[[Tiger Beat]]'' her musical inspirations are [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[unicorn]]s and [[Elvis Presley]].<ref name=\"tigerbeat\">{{cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/video/that-poppy-talks-exclusively-to-tiger-beat/ |title=Fashion, Music and Prom According to Pop Sensation That Poppy |date=March 7, 2016 |website=Tiger Beat |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817154259/http://tigerbeat.com/video/that-poppy-talks-exclusively-to-tiger-beat/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Chesky |first=Allison |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She is a fan of [[Jimmy Eat World]], [[No Doubt]], [[Norma Jean (band)|Norma Jean]], [[Marilyn Manson]], and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]].<ref name=\"next2shine\">{{cite web|url=http://next2shine.com/interview-that-poppy |title=Getting to Know the Imaginative Vision behind That Poppy |last=Then25 |date=March 15, 2016 |website=Next2Shine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617062631/http://next2shine.com/interview-that-poppy |archive-date=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"galore\">{{cite web|url=https://galoremag.com/meet-the-doe-eyed-singer-who-made-thrifting-an-art-project-that-poppy/ |title=Meet The Doe-Eyed Singer Who Made Thrifting An Art Project: That Poppy |date=July 29, 2015 |website=Galore Magazine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526155451/http://galoremag.com/meet-the-doe-eyed-singer-who-made-thrifting-an-art-project-that-poppy/ |archive-date=May 26, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Llewellyn |first=Mallory |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPoppy's identity was initially kept guarded. She explained, \"I don't want people to talk about how old I am; I want them to talk about what I'm making [...] People, especially nowadays, are so obsessed with knowing everything. They'll have to invest their time in finding it.\"<ref name=\"racked2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |title=Meet That Poppy and Wonder If You Too Are Missing the Joke |last=Brooke |first=Eliza |date=April 11, 2016 |website=Racked |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021082726/http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |archive-date=October 21, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Poppy revealed in a statement on Twitter that she had kept her identity guarded due to being a survivor of abuse in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801183256/https:/twitter.com/poppy/status/993430661624020992|title=Poppy on Twitter: \"\u2026 \"|date=August 1, 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2017, Poppy published a book called ''The Gospel of Poppy'', which parodies the Bible and contains \"prayers\" and transcripts of her YouTube videos.\n\n===Reception===\nCritics have both praised the catchiness of Poppy's music and described her persona as distant from reality. ''Racked'' called her \"sweet, but alien\" and \"brightly addictive\".<ref name=\"racked\" /> PopularTV said of her music: \"Paralleling [[Gwen Stefani]] in the [[No Doubt]] era, That Poppy mixes [[punk rock|punk]] with [[ska]]-pop and makes you want to get up and dance.\" The UQ Music Blog described her as \"[[Electra Heart]] meets [[Princess Peach]]\".<ref name=\"uq\">{{cite web |url=http://uqmusicblog.com/2016/02/that-poppy-bubblebath-ep/ |title=That Poppy \u2013 Bubblebath EP |date=February 12, 2016 |website=UQ Music Blog |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422080751/http://uqmusicblog.com/2016/02/that-poppy-bubblebath-ep/ |archive-date=April 22, 2016 |url-status=dead |last=Peterson |first=Tyler |accessdate=March 14, 2017  }}</ref> David Mogendorff, who works in artist content and services for YouTube and Google Play Music, said she has \"a strong J- and K-pop influence\".<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|last=Gibsone |first=Harriet |title=Global grime, political struggle and a Chinese pop explosion \u2013 what will be 2017's music trends? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jan/05/global-grime-political-struggle-and-a-chinese-pop-explosion-what-will-be-2017s-music-trends |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=May 6, 2017 |date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317231047/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jan/05/global-grime-political-struggle-and-a-chinese-pop-explosion-what-will-be-2017s-music-trends |archivedate=March 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPoppy's YouTube channel is often regarded as a commentary on social media. ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' described the tone of the channel, saying, \"...if you have the patience to work your way through all the videos on this channel, certain trends start to emerge. The most obvious is Poppy's fixation with the internet and social media culture, which she claims to love. But far more interesting is the general tone of the videos, which have gotten progressively darker over the last two years.\"<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|last=Oberhaus |first=David |title=This Is Not an Interview with Poppy |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/this-is-not-an-interview-with-poppy |website=Motherboard VICE |accessdate=May 6, 2017|date=January 9, 2017 }}</ref> Gita Jackson of ''[[Kotaku]]'' suggested the videos are a commentary on the experience of being on the Internet, writing, \"In a way, she's made every YouTube video, ever. Her channel is an index of every insincere apology, desperate bid for views and assurance that they couldn't do it without her fans you'll ever see. That Poppy is not only skewering the absurdity of people who make a living as public figures on the internet\u2014she has it out for the entire experience of being online.\" Mogendorff said the videos are \"like social commentary...touch[ing] on the anxieties of modern life\" and \"a really interesting way of communicating, personal but strange\".<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\n''[[V (American magazine)|V Magazine]]'' listed Poppy as part of the new generation of music, saying that \"...her hatched-from-an-egg, [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glenda the Good Witch]] vibes have inspired labels from 'human ASMR' to a one-woman 'digital rabbit hole', none of which seem to stick\".<ref name=\"vmag\">{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Samuel |title=The New Generation in Music|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/new-generation-music/ |website=V Magazine|accessdate=January 23, 2019|date=January 17, 2019 }}</ref> ''[[Paper Magazine|Paper]]'' magazine also listed Poppy as one of the 100 women revolutionizing pop music, noting that \"no matter what Poppy does, we can learn to expect the unexpected.\"<ref name=\"papermag\">{{cite web|last=Love Michael |first=Michael |title=100 Women Revolutionizing Pop|url=http://www.papermag.com/100-women-in-pop-2587872427.html?rebelltitem=65 |website=Paper Magazine|accessdate=January 23, 2019|date=July 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPoppy has spoken in interviews about her gender identity, saying \"I haven't figured it out, but I'd like to stay gender neutral. I don't want to classify myself. I'm just Poppy.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her [[Questioning (sexuality and gender)|gender questioning]] influenced the themes of ''[[Am I a Girl?]]''. In a 2019 interview, she revealed that she identified as a girl, and said that she thinks \"everyone should be able to identify with whatever they choose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flaunt.com/content/poppy|title=Poppy &#124; If Identity Is Currency, Let's Bet The Whole Damned Farm|website=Flaunt Magazine}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Films\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n|2019\n|''A Jester's Tale''\n|Herself\n|For the 2019 Sundance Film Festival.\n|}\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|''Jessie'']]\n|Student\n|Uncredited [[Cameo appearance|cameo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thefutoncritic.com/showatch/jessie/listings|title=Shows A-Z - jessie on disney {{!}} TheFutonCritic.com|website=thefutoncritic.com|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Impulse (TV series)|Impulse]]''\n| Poetry Student\n| Cameo<ref>{{cite web|title=Poppy appears in season 2 of the YouTube Originals series \"Impulse\" |url=https://twitter.com/PoppyUpdate/status/1184634778114543616|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Web===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Web\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Everybody Wants to Be Poppy''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Herself\n| Lead vocal role; 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Internet Famous with Poppy''\n| Lead role; 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[I'm Poppy]]''\n| Lead role<ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Poppy is as weird as its namesake YouTube star, but less intriguing|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/24/16928014/im-poppy-titanic-sinclair-youtube-red-review-sundance-2018|website=The Verge|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127083930/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/24/16928014/im-poppy-titanic-sinclair-youtube-red-review-sundance-2018|archivedate=January 27, 2018|date=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Poppy discography}}\n\n* ''[[Poppy.Computer]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Am I a Girl?]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[I Disagree]]'' (2020)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Gospel Of Poppy'' (2017)\n* ''Genesis One'' (2019)\n* ''Damnation: Poppy's Inferno'' (2020)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Headlining'''\n* [[Poppy.Computer Tour]] (2017\u201318)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/10/06/poppy-debut-album-poppy-computer-tour/ |title=Viral Musician Poppy Releases Debut Album, Will Embark on First-Ever Tour |last=Weiss |first=Geoff |date=October 6, 2017 |website=[[Tubefilter]] |accessdate=November 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034904/http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/10/06/poppy-debut-album-poppy-computer-tour/ |archivedate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Am I a Girl? Tour]] (2018\u201319)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://poppy.church/box-office |accessdate=July 10, 2018|title=Poppy.Church Box Office}}</ref>\n* I Disagree Tour (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1181856915116187648|title=I Disagree Tour - Europe 2020 : On Sale Friday 10AM BST / 11AM CESTpic.twitter.com/VTthGG4QoY|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Co-headlining'''\n* Threesome Tour (2019; with [[Bring Me the Horizon]] and [[Sleeping with Sirens]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://loudwire.com/bring-me-the-horizon-fall-2019-tour-sleeping-with-sirens-poppy/|accessdate=August 8, 2019|title=Threesome Tour}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2016\n| 19 Under 19 Awards\n| Most Influential Song<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7503419/daya-shawn-mendes-tiger-beat-19-under-19|title=Daya, Shawn Mendes & More Nominated for Tiger Beat's 19 Under 19|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| \"Lowlife\"\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2017\n| [[Streamy Awards]]\n| Breakthrough Artist\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Herself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| WOWie Awards\n| Best YouTube Channel<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WorldOfWonder/status/931570205830066178|title=Poppy nominated for Best YouTube Channel|publisher=[[World of Wonder (production company)|World of Wonder]]|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Unicorn Awards\n| Iconic Moment of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|title=Poppy Unicorn Awards Iconic Moment of the Year|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|date=December 16, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216091636/http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|archivedate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|title=Poppy Unicorn Awards Song of the Year|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|date=December 16, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216091636/http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|archivedate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n| \"Computer Boy\"\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Best in Weird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/10th/poppy|title=Poppy Shorty Awards Best in Weird|publisher=[[Shorty Awards]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 16, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190546/http://shortyawards.com/10th/poppy|archivedate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://impoppy.com/}}\n* {{imdb name|8824909}}\n* [http://www.businessinsider.com/poppy-youtube-religion-2017-11 ''Business Insider'' article, December 5, 2017]\n\n{{Poppy|state=expanded}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poppy}}\n[[Category:Poppy (singer)| ]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Ambient composers]]\n[[Category:Ambient musicians]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Electropop musicians]]\n[[Category:Female YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Music YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mad Decent artists]]\n[[Category:American religious leaders]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:American female heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Nu metal singers]]\n[[Category:Kawaii metal musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer and YouTube personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Poppy\n| image              = Poppy - 2016 (portrait).jpg\n| caption            = Poppy in 2016\n| birth_name         = Moriah Rose Pereira\n| birth_date         = <!--Please don't remove the birthday anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but matter is that she was born on January 1, 1995. Professional biographer Neil Z. Yeung of Apple Music has even attributed her birth to this date.-->{{Birth date and age|1995|01|01}}\n| birth_place        = <!--Please don't remove the birthplace anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but the fact of the matter is that she was born near Boston.-->{{nowrap|near [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pandell|first=Lexi|title=Welcome to Poppy's World|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|journal=Wired|accessdate=February 15, 2018|date=June 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Singer, [[YouTuber]]\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| website            = {{URL|impoppy.com}}\n| signature          = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| alias              = {{flatlist|\n* That Poppy\n* Poppy Chan\n* {{nowrap|Moriah Poppy}}\n}}\n| instrument         = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n* synthesizer\n* electronic organ\n}}\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Electropop]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[art pop]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[nu metal]]\n* [[kawaii metal]]<ref>{{cite web \n|last1=PASBANI |first1=ROBERT |title=IRONBUNNY Is The Japanese Metal Group with A Cyborg Guitarist You've Been Waiting For |url=https://metalinjection.net/av/new-music/ironbunny-is-the-japanese-metal-group-with-a-cyborg-guitarist-youve-been-waiting-for |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n* I'm Poppy\n* {{nowrap|[[Mad Decent]]}}\n* [[Sumerian Records|Sumerian]]\n}}\n| associated_acts               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Diplo]]\n* [[Fever 333]]\n* [[Grimes]]\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| channel_name     = thatPoppyTV\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* Entertainment\n* [[internet culture]]\n* satire\n* pop culture\n* music\n}}\n| silver_button    = yes\n| silver_year      = 2016\n| gold_button      = yes\n| gold_year        = 2017\n| subscribers      = 2.58 million\n| subscriber_date  = September 10, 2019\n| views            = 478+ million\n| view_date        = February 3, 2020\n| ages             =\n| stats_update     = \n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Moriah Rose Pereira''' (born January 1, 1995),<ref>{{cite news|title=Poppy is a disturbing internet meme seen by millions. Can she become a pop sensation?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|newspaper=The Guardian|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127205557/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|archivedate=January 27, 2018|date=December 11, 2017|last1=Hunt|first1=Elle}}</ref> known professionally as '''Poppy''', is an American singer, songwriter, [[YouTuber]], and religious leader.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/poppy-youtube-religion-2017-11|title=Meet Poppy, the 22-year-old YouTube star who has already inspired her own religion|first=Zo\u00eb|last=Bernard|website=Business Insider}}</ref><ref name=auto/> In 2013, Poppy moved to [[Los Angeles]] where she rose to prominence while working with director and musician [[Titanic Sinclair]] who helped her enhance her YouTube presence by making short performance art videos and music videos. In 2015, she signed a recording contract with [[Island Records]], subsequently releasing her debut extended play, ''[[Bubblebath (EP)|Bubblebath]]'', as '''That Poppy'''.\n\nIn late 2016, Poppy became the face of [[Sanrio]]'s \"Hello Sanrio\" collection.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|title=Welcome to Poppy's World|last=Pandell|first=Lexi|work=WIRED|access-date=October 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020005326/https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/|archivedate=October 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In the summer of 2017, she signed to [[Mad Decent]], and in October released her first studio album, ''[[Poppy.Computer]]''. To promote the album she embarked on [[Poppy.Computer Tour|her first tour]], which consisted of 34 North American cities separated by shows in London and Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/slideshows/poppy-at-slims-oct-27-2017/|title=Poppy at Slim's Oct. 26, 2017 \u2013 By geoffrey-smith-ii \u2013 October 30, 2017 \u2013 SF Weekly|date=October 30, 2017|work=SF Weekly|access-date=November 12, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112185300/http://www.sfweekly.com/slideshows/poppy-at-slims-oct-27-2017/|archivedate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, she released her [[web television]] series, ''[[I'm Poppy]]'', and her second studio album, ''[[Am I a Girl?]].'' On January 10, 2020, [[Sumerian Records]] published her third studio album, ''[[I Disagree]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/poppy-concrete-sumerian-records/|title=Poppy debuts new track \"Concrete,\" signs with Sumerian Records|last=Shoemaker|first=Whitney|date=August 22, 2019|website=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|altpress.com]]|language=English|quote=After dropping teasers throughout the week, Poppy has unveiled her latest track 'Concrete' and announced her signing to Sumerian Records.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/poppy_goes_metal_with_new_album_i_disagree|title=Poppy Goes Metal with New Album 'I Disagree|last=Thiessen|first=Brock|date=October 4, 2019|website=[[Exclaim!|exclaim.ca]]|language=English|quote=The album is due out on January 10 via Sumerian Records, and it promises to be quite the departure for Poppy.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMoriah Rose Pereira was born near [[Boston]], Massachusetts<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|title=Poppy is a disturbing internet meme seen by millions. Can she become a pop sensation?|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127205557/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/poppy-youtube-meme-pop-sensation-titanic-sinclair-moriah-pereira|archivedate=January 27, 2018}}</ref><!--Please don't remove the birthday anymore. There's been a lot of disputes but the fact of the matter is that she was born on January 1, 1995. Professional biographer Neil Z. Yeung of [[Apple Music]] has even attributed her birth to this date.--> on January 1, 1995. She grew up in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> She recalls wanting to be a [[The Rockettes|Rockette]] as a child and grew up dancing,<ref name=\"amp\">{{cite web |url=http://923amp.cbslocal.com/2016/03/01/that-poppy-talks-princesses-unicorns-and-real-life-experiences-with-niko/ |title=That Poppy Talks 'Princesses, Unicorns, and Real Life Experiences' with Niko |author=Niko |date=March 1, 2016 |website=92.3 AMP Radio |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816111853/http://923amp.cbslocal.com/2016/03/01/that-poppy-talks-princesses-unicorns-and-real-life-experiences-with-niko/ |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 14, 2017  }}</ref> which she did for 11 years.<ref name=\"jakestake\">{{cite web|url=http://jakes-take.com/2015/07/the-five-question-challenge-with-that-poppy/ |title=The Five Question Challenge with That Poppy |date=July 7, 2015 |website=Jake's Take |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817041002/http://jakes-take.com/2015/07/the-five-question-challenge-with-that-poppy/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Elyachar |first=Jacob |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref> She is naturally a brunette.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.wetheunicorns.com/features/age-real-name-height-moriah-pereira-instagram/|title=Who Is Poppy? Everything You Need To Know About The Mysterious YouTuber|website=amp.wetheunicorns.com|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 18, Poppy left home for Los Angeles in pursuit of an entertainment career.\n\n==Career==\n===2012\u20132014: Early performances===\nPrior to 2014, Poppy performed at [[social media]] festivals, including [[VidCon]] in June 2012 and [[DigiTour Media|DigiTour]] in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2013/06/poppy-and-sam-pepper-interview |title=YouTube Stars Poppy & Sam Pepper Chat New Music, Translate Phrase \"Turnt Up\" |date=June 11, 2013 |website=Fuse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305200004/http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2013/06/poppy-and-sam-pepper-interview |archive-date=March 5, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> Poppy began her musical career by singing cover songs on the internet.\n\n===2015\u20132016: YouTube partnership with Titanic Sinclair, ''Bubblebath'', ''3:36 (Music to Sleep To)''===\nPoppy moved to Los Angeles in 2013 to pursue her musical career.<ref name=\"racked\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |title=Parsing the Aesthetics of That Poppy, Pop Singer and Internet Enigma |date=April 11, 2016 |website=Racked |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718003313/http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |archive-date=July 18, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Brooke |first=Eliza |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref> There she teamed up with former [[Music video director|director]] Corey Michael Mixter,<ref>{{cite web|title=Corey Michael Mixter|url=https://genius.com/artists/corey-michael-mixter|website=Genius|accessdate=October 6, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021105/https://genius.com/artists/Corey-michael-mixter|archivedate=October 7, 2017}}</ref> best known by his stage name [[Titanic Sinclair]], to make a series of abstract promotional videos on a YouTube channel originally titled \"thatPoppyTV\". The channel is now simply known as \"Poppy\". As of April 2018, the channel is actively uploading videos and has attracted a large audience. In 2015, she signed to [[Island Records]] under the name That Poppy and released her debut song, \"Everybody Wants to Be Poppy\", in June of that year.<ref name=\"island Records\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islandrecords.com/news/that-poppy-releases-everybody-wants-to-be-poppy/ |title=That Poppy Releases 'Everybody Wants to Be Poppy' |date=June 23, 2015 |website=Island Records |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105004141/http://www.islandrecords.com/news/that-poppy-releases-everybody-wants-to-be-poppy/ |archive-date=November 5, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She performed at the Corona Capital Festival in November 2015.<ref name=\"tono\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tono.tv/fotos-poppy-en-el-corona-capital-2015/ |title=Fotos: Poppy en el Corona Capital 2015 |date=November 24, 2015 |website=TONO |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308150224/http://www.tono.tv/fotos-poppy-en-el-corona-capital-2015/ |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |last=Fran\u00e7ois |first=Toni |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"axscc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.axs.com/corona-capital-announce-their-2015-festival-lineup-56098 |title=Corona Capital announce their 2015 festival lineup |date=June 1, 2015 |website=AXS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308143217/http://www.axs.com/corona-capital-announce-their-2015-festival-lineup-56098 |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |last=Lopez |first=Ashleyan |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She released the song, \"[[Lowlife (Poppy song)|Lowlife]]\", a month after releasing her first single \"Everybody Wants to Be Poppy\" and released her first EP, a four-track pop record called ''[[Bubblebath (EP)|Bubblebath]]'', on [[Island Records|Island]] in February 2016.<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{Citation|last=That Poppy|title=Bubblebath|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Bubblebath-Explicit-That-Poppy/dp/B01BKTUG9O/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&qid=1466978210&sr=8-2&keywords=that+poppy&linkCode=ll1&linkId=185874ad00b207a936478b6c14c683ac |accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.circa.com/story/2017/07/18/hollywood/youtube-star-that-poppy-talks-career-live|title=YouTube sensation That Poppy gave us the most wonderfully bizarre interview ever about her life and career|access-date=July 19, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728090019/https://www.circa.com/story/2017/07/18/hollywood/youtube-star-that-poppy-talks-career-live|archivedate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> The EP consists of four songs; [[Lowlife (song)|\"Lowlife]]\", \"Money\", \"Altar\", and \"American Kids\". In August 2016, she released a series of advertisements for the shoe company [[Steve Madden (company)|Steve Madden]] on her channel as a part of its ''Steve Madden Music'' program.<ref name=\"stevemaddensite\">{{cite web |author=Steve Madden |title=That Poppy: STEVE MADDEN |url=http://www.stevemadden.com/content.jsp?pageName=ThatPoppy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816184347/http://www.stevemadden.com/content.jsp?pageName=ThatPoppy |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 16, 2016 |website=Steve Madden |accessdate=May 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, Poppy released an [[Experimental music|experimental]] [[ambient music]] album called ''[[3:36 (Music to Sleep To)]]'', composed by Titanic Sinclair and herself, with assistance from [[Polysomnography|polysomnographists]] from the [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] [[Washington University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impoppy.bandcamp.com/album/3-36-music-to-sleep-to |title=3:36 (Music To Sleep To) |website=Bandcamp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308133746/https://impoppy.bandcamp.com/album/3-36-music-to-sleep-to |archive-date=March 8, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, she became the face of Japanese retailer [[Sanrio]]'s first \"Hello Sanrio\" collection.\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''Poppy.Computer'', Poppy.Church, Mars Argo lawsuit, and ''Am I a Girl?''===\n[[File:Poppy Tour.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy performing live at YouTube Space in Los Angeles]]\n[[File:That Poppy.jpg|thumb|During the ''Poppy.Computer'' Tour, October 2017]]\nIn February 2017, Poppy starred in a series of videos for [[Comedy Central]] called \"Internet Famous with Poppy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s7JnLRwAdAI|title=Internet Famous with Poppy \u2013 Brandon Wardell|date=February 13, 2017|via=YouTube|publisher=Comedy Central|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> That September, she won a Streamy award in the category 'Breakthrough Artist'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abrams Artists Agency Signs Viral Musician Poppy |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/11/26/abrams-artists-agency-signs-viral-musician-poppy-youtube-tour/ |accessdate=December 23, 2018 |work=Tubefilter |date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Poppy 10 31 2018 -28 (46548657641).jpg|thumb|Poppy performing live at The Wiltern in Los Angeles, California, on Wednesday, October 31, 2018]]\n\nPoppy's debut studio album, ''[[Poppy.Computer]]'', was released on October 6, 2017 by [[Mad Decent]]. Her first concert tour, the 36-city [[Poppy.Computer Tour|''Poppy.Computer'' Tour]], started on October 19 in [[Vancouver]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} In November, Poppy announced that her second studio album was \"almost ready\", and that she was going to Japan again to finish it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://1033ampradio.radio.com/2017/11/22/poppy-is-almost-done-with-second-album-more-tour-dates-coming/ |title=Poppy's interview for 103.3 AMP |website=103.3 AMP |accessdate=November 22, 2017 |date=November 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033335/http://1033ampradio.radio.com/2017/11/22/poppy-is-almost-done-with-second-album-more-tour-dates-coming/ |archivedate=December 1, 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPoppy made her ''[[YouTube Rewind]]'' debut in 2017, and was one of the few content creators to get their own lines.\n\nIn March 2018, Poppy performed at the Japanese pop music festival, Popspring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popspring.jp/2018/poppy.html |title=Poppy Popspring |website=Popspring.jp |accessdate=April 7, 2018 |date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2018, Sinclair's former partner [[Mars Argo]] filed a 44-page lawsuit in [[United States District Court for the Central District of California|Central California court]] against Sinclair and Poppy alleging copyright infringement, stating that Sinclair based Poppy's online persona on hers, as well as emotional and physical abuse Sinclair had allegedly subjected to her in the period after their separation and the subsequent abandonment of the project.<ref name=\"tmzlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=YouTube Feud: Mars Sues Titanic and ThatPoppy: You Jacked My Identity!!!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/17/youtube-legal-feud-titanic-sinclair-mars-argo-thatpoppy/|publisher=[[TMZ]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> On May 7, Poppy made a public statement about the \"frivolous\" lawsuit, saying Argo was attempting to manipulate her psychologically. She called the suit a \"publicity campaign\" and a \"desperate grab for fame\".<ref name=\"billboardlawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Poppy Responds to Mars Argo Copyright Suit, Calls It 'Desperate Grab for Fame'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8454780/poppy-responds-mars-argo-copyright-lawsuit-desperate-grab-for-fame/|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref> The Sinclair case was settled out of court on September 14 \"with no money exchanging hands\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/poppy-and-manager-titanic-sinclair-settle-lawsuit-with-mars-argo-2428225|title=Poppy and collaborator Titanic Sinclair settle lawsuit with Mars Argo|work=NME|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/lawsuit-poppy-titanic-sinclair-dismissed/|title=Lawsuit against YouTube personality Poppy dismissed|date=September 18, 2018|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Argo released a statement in January 2019 that all rights to Mars Argo had been assigned to her as part of the settlement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/marsargo/status/1083047047966539776|title=pic.twitter.com/4P670nKPuj|first=Mars|last=Argo|date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The copyright case against Poppy was dismissed.\n[[File:Poppy 10 31 2018 -2 (45635254575).jpg|thumb|left|Poppy performing at [[Pellissier Building and Wiltern Theatre|The Wiltern]] during her [[Am I a Girl? Tour|''Am I a Girl?'' Tour]]]]\nOn July 6, 2018, Poppy released a cover of [[Gary Numan]]'s song \"[[Metal (song)|Metal]]\" as a single on all digital platforms.<ref name=\"iTunesMetal\">{{cite web|title=iTunes Metal|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/metal-single/1405863089|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref> On July 27, she released the first single for the album ''[[Am I a Girl?]]'' titled \"In a Minute\".<ref name=\"iTunesInAMinute\">{{cite web|title=iTunes in a Minute \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-a-minute-single/1416243366|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=July 27, 2018}}</ref> She released the album's second single \"[[Time Is Up (song)|Time Is Up]]\", which features American DJ [[Diplo]], on August 22.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes Time Is Up \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/time-is-up-feat-diplo-single/1425178835|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/poppy-and-diplo-team-up-for-new-song-time-is-up-listen/amp/|title=Poppy and Diplo Team Up for New Song 'Time Is Up': Listen |website=Pitchfork|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/dance/8471646/poppy-diplo-time-is-up|title=Poppy and Diplo Celebrate the Robot Takeover On 'Time Is Up': Watch|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref> she released \"Fashion After All\" on October 12.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fashion After All|date=October 12, 2018|url=https://open.spotify.com/track/1fG2o4l6jDPDJPdWIMoG3u?si=bunvY-NfQFaYW1zMfh7Xgg|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Fashion After All by Poppy|date=October 12, 2018|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/fashion-after-all/1438151959?i=1438151960|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> \"Hard Feelings\" was released on October 19 and \"X\" was released on October 25.  In September 2018, Poppy announced on her social media that she was already working on her third studio album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1042407821835468802|title=Poppy's Twitter September 19th, 2018 |website=Twitter |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |date=September 19, 2018 }}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref> On September 11, Poppy's Twitter account announced an album release and costume party for October 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1039645459009204224|title=Poppy's Twitter September 11th, 2018 |website=Twitter |accessdate=October 8, 2018 |date=September 11, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Poppy began to drop hints about a new project and website called Poppy.Church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://poppy.church/|title=Poppy.Church|website=poppy.church|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> At first, the purpose of the website was not known, as it only featured a cryptic message and an opportunity to enter one's phone number. After a few months, however, the purpose of the site was made clear. Every day at 3:36 PDT, certain people who entered their phone number would receive a link to join the Church. There they could fill out a profile, create an avatar, and pledge their allegiance to her. As of August 24, there is an Atrium, which acts as a chatroom, a theater, a gallery which changes weekly, a lobby like another chatroom, a bulletin board with announcements, a personal report page, a box office selling tickets for Poppy's ''Am I a Girl?'' tour,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://poppy.church/box-office|title=Box Office|website=poppy.church|access-date=July 30, 2018}}</ref> a backpack, and a settings page to edit contact information and character. On August 23, room invites were sent out to members of the Church who were showing \"Faith, Dedication, and Loyalty\". There are 100,000 rooms, with 1,000 halls connecting to the corresponding 100 rooms in that hall. (For example, Hall No. 1 has rooms 1\u2013100, Hall No. 2 has rooms 101\u2013200, and so on.) Members of the Church can visit each other's rooms, leave comments on their walls, and access provided social media.\n\nPoppy attended the [[American Music Awards of 2018|2018 American Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/poppy-black-mask-2018-american-music-awards/amp|title=Poppy Wore a Black Latex Mask to the 2018 American Music Awards|website=wmagazine.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/poppy/ama-outfit-mask/|title=People Are LOSING IT Over What Poppy Wore to the AMAs|website=amp.wetheunicorns.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/american-music-awards-2018-worst-13392860.amp|title=American Music Awards 2018 \u2013 The Worst Dressed|date=October 10, 2018|work=mirror|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> After winning the Breakthrough Artist in 2017, Poppy returned to the [[Streamy Awards]] in 2018 as a presenter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/10/23/youtuber-poppy-walks-the-streamys-red-carpet-with-three-dates-in-gimp-suits-8066620/|title=YouTuber Poppy walks the Streamys red carpet with three dates in gimp suits|date=October 23, 2018|work=Metro|access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/poppy/streamys-gimps-outfit/|title=You won't believe what Poppy took to the Streamy Awards...|work=We The Unicorns|access-date=October 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Genesis 1'', ''A Jester's Tale'', ''Choke'' and ''I Disagree''===\n\nOn January 8, 2019, Poppy announced a graphic novel through Z2 Comics entitled ''Genesis 1'', which was released to comic book stores on July 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/poppy-moves-comics-genesis-1-graphic-novel-1174634|title=Musician Poppy Moves to Comics for 'Genesis 1' Graphic Novel|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The graphic novel tells the origin of Poppy. The description on Z2 Comics' website reads \"Is she a girl? Is she a machine? Is she humanity's redemption, or its damnation? Don't be scared \u2013 either way, she is Poppy\u2026 and you love Poppy. Witness the genesis of the internet phenomenon in this original graphic novel, bundled with an exclusive brand new album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comiccrusaders.com/poppy-announces-first-ever-graphic-novel-genesis-1-available-july-2019/|title=POPPY ANNOUNCES FIRST EVER GRAPHIC NOVEL 'GENESIS 1' AVAILABLE JULY 2019 \u2013 Comic Crusaders|first=Al|last=Mega|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> It was co-written by Poppy, Titanic Sinclair and Ryan Cady, with art by Masa Minoura and Ian McGinty. She elaborated in an interview with Gigwise that the album released with the graphic novel, titled ''I C U: Music to Read To'', is an ambient music album meant to be listened to while reading.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.gigwise.com/features/3304522/poppy-interview-new-coming-book-release-and-companion-album|title=Poppy talks new ambient release, being a religious leader, + embracing heavy metal|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' announced Poppy would star in the [[augmented-reality]] experience ''A Jester's Tale'' created and directed by Asad J. Malik. It was produced by [[RYOT]] and 1RIC, premiering at the Sundance Film Festival as part of the New Frontier program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8494669/poppy-a-jesters-tale-ar-experience-sundance-2019|title=Poppy to Star in Augmented Reality Experience 'A Jester's Tale,' Premiering at Sundance 2019: Exclusive|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> The storyline \"transports viewers inside a child's bedroom to meet a cast of character holograms\". Later that month in an interview to ''[[Forbes]]'', Poppy announced her new single and video called \"Voicemail\", produced and directed by Titanic Sinclair. It was released on January 31.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/01/25/poppy-voicemail-new-single-sundance-2019-interview/|title=Poppy Shares Details on New Single 'Voicemail,' WWE Collaboration, AR Experience at Sundance & More|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> After attending the [[IHeartRadio Music Awards|iHeartRadio awards]] in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehollywoodgossip.com/gallery/that-poppy-2016-iheartradio-music-awards/|title=That Poppy: 2016 iHeartRadio Music Awards|last=Lynch|first=Kelly|date=April 4, 2016|website=The Hollywood Gossip|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> she returned in 2019 wearing a dress designed by [[Viktor & Rolf]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stealherstyle.net/2019/03/15/poppy-2019-iheartradio-music-awards/|title=Poppy: 2019 iHeartRadio Music Awards|date=March 15, 2019|website=Steal Her Style|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/vogueworld/article/poppy-viktor-and-rolf-couture-iheartradio-awards|title=Poppy Wears Viktor and Rolf's 2019 Couture to the iHeartRadio Music Awards 2019|last=Okwodu|first=Janelle|website=Vogue|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> and sat front row at their fashion show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/poppy-iheart-radio-viktor-rolf-meme-dress|title=Poppy Shows Up at iHeartRadio Music Awards in Fashion Week's Most Memed Dress|last=Eckardt|first=Stephanie|website=wmagazine.com|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/singer-poppy-attends-the-victor-rolf-haute-couture-fall-news-photo/1159864098|title=Singer Poppy attends the Victor&Rolf Haute Couture Fall/Winter 2019...|website=Getty Images|language=en-us|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Poppy revealed plans for a movie and her own [[music streaming]] service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stockx.com/news/thats-five-with-poppy/|title=That's Five with Poppy|date=March 15, 2019|website=StockX News|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> She attended the ''Billboard'' Music Awards. Her song \"Scary Mask\" was released on May 29, and featured American rock band [[Fever 333]]. The song was included on her second EP, ''Choke'', which was on released on June 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5d001aa3b8bad3671fd7bfc5/|title=Poppy Is The Face of Nu-Metal in 2019 {{!}} BUILD Series NYC|website=Build Series|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, Poppy announced that her third studio album entitled ''[[I Disagree]]'' would be released on January 10, 2020 through [[Sumerian Records]]. The title track was released as the second single from the album (following \"[[Concrete (Poppy song)|Concrete]]\" in August) on October 4 alongside the album pre-order. The album continues the [[Heavy metal music|metal]] sound featured on her 2019 EP ''Choke'' and the latter half of ''Am I a Girl?''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wallofsoundau.com/2019/10/04/poppy-announces-new-album-i-disagree-unleashed-the-title-track-single/|title=Poppy Announces New Album \"I Disagree\" + Unleashed The Title Track Single|date=October 4, 2019|website=Wall Of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> \"[[Bloodmoney]]\" was released as the third single from the album on November 6, 2019, and \"Fill The Crown\" was released as the fourth single from the album on December 11, 2019. The final single from the album, \"Anything Like Me,\" was released alongside the album and the music video for the track on 10 January 2020. \n\nOn December 28, Poppy released a statement confirming that she and Sinclair parted ways. She accused him of glamorizing suicide and using this to manipulate her, alleging she and Sinclair's former collaborator Mars Argo suffered similar psychological abuse.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/poppy-titanic-sinclair-accuses-manipulative-patterns-2591556|title=Poppy parts ways with Titanic Sinclair, accuses him of \"manipulative patterns\"|last=Lavin|first=Will|work=NME|date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2020, Poppy announced her second graphic novel, titled ''Damnation: Poppy's Inferno''. It will be published on July 21, 2020 alongside a soundtrack album, ''Music to Scream To''.\n\n==YouTube==\nPoppy's YouTube channel was created on October 6, 2011, and her earliest video is from November 2014, an abstract skit called ''Poppy Eats Cotton Candy'', directed by Titanic Sinclair. The videos are described by their producer Sinclair as \"a combination of [[Andy Warhol]]'s pop accessibility, [[David Lynch]]'s creepiness, and [[Tim Burton]]'s zany comedic tone\".<ref name=\"racked\" /> The channel has been discussed by other YouTubers, including [[PewDiePie]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vdGiqRjTd34 |title=I'M POPPY! |last=PewDiePie |date=December 3, 2016 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223113628/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vdGiqRjTd34 |archive-date=December 23, 2016 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017}}</ref> [[Social Repose]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Social Repose|title=Goth Reacts to Poppy|date=October 14, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XJg9uzbXoCk|accessdate=May 22, 2017}}</ref> Night Mind,<ref>{{Citation|last=Night Mind|title=Who Is Poppy?|date=July 7, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NmXQKMjEC8E|accessdate=July 18, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822074146/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NmXQKMjEC8E|archivedate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> the [[MatPat|Film Theorists]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CqdE2EKhJG4 |title=Poppy's Hidden Conspiracy EXPOSED! |date=January 24, 2017 |website= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312044551/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CqdE2EKhJG4 |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017 |author=The Film Theorists}}</ref> Reaction Time, and the [[Fine Brothers]] on their ''[[React (media franchise)|React]]'' series. She starred in an episode in which she reacts to children reacting to her videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xqH3KaW25AA |title=Poppy Reacts to Kids React to Poppy |date=February 22, 2017 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307102916/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xqH3KaW25AA |archive-date=March 7, 2017 |url-status=live |access-date=March 14, 2017 |author=[[The Fine Brothers]]}}</ref> She has also appeared in an episode of the acclaimed web series ''[[Good Mythical Morning]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kls6wSVqbrY|title=Will It Poppy?|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nSinclair alludes in an interview that Poppy's character in the promotional videos presented itself to him as an [[Android (robot)|android]] and how some of the concept relates to the [[uncanny valley]] hypothesis.<ref name=\"Dom\">{{Citation|last=Dom's Sketch Cast|title=Titanic Sinclair {{!}} DSC Interview|date=October 31, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l81ienfgzss|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref> Poppy has stated that her YouTube videos tell a story.<ref>{{Citation|last=NME|title=Poppy on 'Am I A Girl', Grimes, Marilyn Manson and the future|date=October 26, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYqyAHfRatM|access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAside from her abstract promotional videos, Poppy's channel features her original music,<ref>{{Citation|last=Poppy |title=Poppy \u2013 Computer Boy (Official Video) |date=May 19, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Ao5mg11xIk |accessdate=May 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519171542/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5Ao5mg11xIk&gl=US&hl=en |archivedate=May 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://popcrush.com/poppy-lets-make-a-video-watch/|title=Poppy Makes a Video For 'Let's Make a Video'|website=PopCrush|access-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711204401/http://popcrush.com/poppy-lets-make-a-video-watch/|archivedate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> various covers, and [[acoustic music|acoustic]] versions of her songs.\n\nPoppy's friend Charlotte, a celebrity-interviewing [[mannequin]] with a [[Speech synthesis|synthetic voice]], is a recurring character. She usually appears interacting with Poppy but also on her own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/poppy-youtube-cult/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901112147/https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/poppy-youtube-cult/|url-status=dead|title=The Cult Appeal of Poppy, the Perfect Pop Idol of the Future|date=August 16, 2017|archivedate=September 1, 2017|website=The Daily Dot}}</ref> She appears to have developed a drug and jealousy problem after Poppy became famous, which strains their relationship,<ref name=wired>{{cite journal | url = https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/ | title = Welcome to Poppy's World | date = June 4, 2017 | accessdate = June 5, 2017 | journal = Wired | author = Lexi Pandell | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170604213635/https://www.wired.com/2017/06/shes-poppy/ | archivedate = June 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDJjDZ_PuPY&list=PLqt12vbt3qkcCPIX-NjyftjMtIea1b5nA|title=Poppy is Over|last=Poppy|date=April 12, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> although Charlotte became Poppy's opening act for her 2017\u20132018 [[Poppy.Computer Tour|''Poppy.Computer'' Tour]]. Other characters include Charlotte's son, a boy mannequin who has taken the brunt of abuse at the hands of his mother during a drugged stupor; Plant (voiced by Sinclair), a potted basil plant who is one of Poppy's closest friends and biggest supporter; and Skeleton (also voiced by Sinclair), a plastic model skeleton who is revealed as Charlotte's drug dealer.\n\nThe channel also has an animated promotional [[miniseries]] called ''Everybody Wants to Be Poppy'', directed by Titanic Sinclair and illustrated by Melanie Foreman, which stars Poppy as herself, Titanic Sinclair as Rex, actor [[Matt Bennett]] as Pho, Canadian singer-songwriter [[Simon Wilcox]] as Phoebe, and Los Angeles-based photographer Sam McGuire as Wyatt. The series documents Poppy and Rex's journey as they attempt to find a \"magical [[kale]] [[smoothie]]\".<ref name=\"animated\">{{cite web|title='Everybody Wants to be Poppy' Episode: 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-PTVaWj-yuE|via=YouTube|date=June 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==''I'm Poppy'' series==\n{{Main|I'm Poppy}}\n''[[I'm Poppy]]'', a short film and the first episode of a television series of the same name written and directed by Titanic Sinclair, made its world premiere on January 23 at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival]]. In it, Poppy leaves the Internet for the real world and confronts the pitfalls of fame, including cults, deranged fans, Satan, and her bitter rival Charlotte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/2018-festival-shorts-indie-episodic-special-events|title=SUNDANCE INSTITUTE ANNOUNCES INDIE EPISODIC, SHORTS & SPECIAL EVENT SELECTIONS FOR 2018 SUNDANCE FILM FESTIVAL|website=sundance.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Poppy\" Will Be the Weirdest Thing Ever on YouTube Red|url= https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/im-poppy-youtube-red-release-date-trailer-1202669317 |work= Variety |accessdate=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180124071013/http://variety.com/2018/digital/news/im-poppy-youtube-red-release-date-trailer-1202669317/|archivedate=January 24, 2018|date= January 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nPoppy explains that her stage name originated as a nickname a friend used to call her. After her friend persistently introduced her as \"Poppy\", the name stuck.<ref>{{cite web|title=#GIRLTALK: Official interview with singer That POPPY|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_8XSVlDkhPQ|via=YouTube|accessdate=October 11, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723172012/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_8XSVlDkhPQ|archivedate=July 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPoppy has described herself as a \"[[kawaii]] [[Barbie]] child\".<ref name=\"next2shine\" /><ref name=\"ladygunn\">{{cite web|url=http://ladygunn.com/music/sugar-and-spice-a-cute-chat-with-that-poppy |title=Suggar and Spice: A Cute Chat With That Poppy! |date=October 22, 2015 |website=Ladygunn |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028145807/http://ladygunn.com/music/sugar-and-spice-a-cute-chat-with-that-poppy |archive-date=October 28, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Hardy |first=Alyssa |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She has described her music style as \"music [that] makes you want to rule the world.\" Poppy states that she drew inspiration from genres such as [[J-pop]] and [[K-pop]], as well as [[reggae]]. She recalls beginning to write music in 2012. She told ''[[Tiger Beat]]'' her musical inspirations are [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[unicorn]]s and [[Elvis Presley]].<ref name=\"tigerbeat\">{{cite web|url=http://tigerbeat.com/video/that-poppy-talks-exclusively-to-tiger-beat/ |title=Fashion, Music and Prom According to Pop Sensation That Poppy |date=March 7, 2016 |website=Tiger Beat |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817154259/http://tigerbeat.com/video/that-poppy-talks-exclusively-to-tiger-beat/ |archive-date=August 17, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Chesky |first=Allison |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> She is a fan of [[Jimmy Eat World]], [[No Doubt]], [[Norma Jean (band)|Norma Jean]], [[Marilyn Manson]], and [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]].<ref name=\"next2shine\">{{cite web|url=http://next2shine.com/interview-that-poppy |title=Getting to Know the Imaginative Vision behind That Poppy |last=Then25 |date=March 15, 2016 |website=Next2Shine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617062631/http://next2shine.com/interview-that-poppy |archive-date=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"galore\">{{cite web|url=https://galoremag.com/meet-the-doe-eyed-singer-who-made-thrifting-an-art-project-that-poppy/ |title=Meet The Doe-Eyed Singer Who Made Thrifting An Art Project: That Poppy |date=July 29, 2015 |website=Galore Magazine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526155451/http://galoremag.com/meet-the-doe-eyed-singer-who-made-thrifting-an-art-project-that-poppy/ |archive-date=May 26, 2016 |url-status=live |last=Llewellyn |first=Mallory |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPoppy's identity was initially kept guarded. She explained, \"I don't want people to talk about how old I am; I want them to talk about what I'm making [...] People, especially nowadays, are so obsessed with knowing everything. They'll have to invest their time in finding it.\"<ref name=\"racked2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |title=Meet That Poppy and Wonder If You Too Are Missing the Joke |last=Brooke |first=Eliza |date=April 11, 2016 |website=Racked |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021082726/http://www.racked.com/2016/4/11/11394848/that-poppy-interview |archive-date=October 21, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Poppy revealed in a statement on Twitter that she had kept her identity guarded due to being a survivor of abuse in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801183256/https:/twitter.com/poppy/status/993430661624020992|title=Poppy on Twitter: \"\u2026 \"|date=August 1, 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2017, Poppy published a book called ''The Gospel of Poppy'', which parodies the Bible and contains \"prayers\" and transcripts of her YouTube videos.\n\n===Reception===\nCritics have both praised the catchiness of Poppy's music and described her persona as distant from reality. ''Racked'' called her \"sweet, but alien\" and \"brightly addictive\".<ref name=\"racked\" /> PopularTV said of her music: \"Paralleling [[Gwen Stefani]] in the [[No Doubt]] era, That Poppy mixes [[punk rock|punk]] with [[ska]]-pop and makes you want to get up and dance.\" The UQ Music Blog described her as \"[[Electra Heart]] meets [[Princess Peach]]\".<ref name=\"uq\">{{cite web |url=http://uqmusicblog.com/2016/02/that-poppy-bubblebath-ep/ |title=That Poppy \u2013 Bubblebath EP |date=February 12, 2016 |website=UQ Music Blog |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422080751/http://uqmusicblog.com/2016/02/that-poppy-bubblebath-ep/ |archive-date=April 22, 2016 |url-status=dead |last=Peterson |first=Tyler |accessdate=March 14, 2017  }}</ref> David Mogendorff, who works in artist content and services for YouTube and Google Play Music, said she has \"a strong J- and K-pop influence\".<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|last=Gibsone |first=Harriet |title=Global grime, political struggle and a Chinese pop explosion \u2013 what will be 2017's music trends? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jan/05/global-grime-political-struggle-and-a-chinese-pop-explosion-what-will-be-2017s-music-trends |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=May 6, 2017 |date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317231047/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jan/05/global-grime-political-struggle-and-a-chinese-pop-explosion-what-will-be-2017s-music-trends |archivedate=March 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPoppy's YouTube channel is often regarded as a commentary on social media. ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' described the tone of the channel, saying, \"...if you have the patience to work your way through all the videos on this channel, certain trends start to emerge. The most obvious is Poppy's fixation with the internet and social media culture, which she claims to love. But far more interesting is the general tone of the videos, which have gotten progressively darker over the last two years.\"<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web|last=Oberhaus |first=David |title=This Is Not an Interview with Poppy |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/this-is-not-an-interview-with-poppy |website=Motherboard VICE |accessdate=May 6, 2017|date=January 9, 2017 }}</ref> Gita Jackson of ''[[Kotaku]]'' suggested the videos are a commentary on the experience of being on the Internet, writing, \"In a way, she's made every YouTube video, ever. Her channel is an index of every insincere apology, desperate bid for views and assurance that they couldn't do it without her fans you'll ever see. That Poppy is not only skewering the absurdity of people who make a living as public figures on the internet\u2014she has it out for the entire experience of being online.\" Mogendorff said the videos are \"like social commentary...touch[ing] on the anxieties of modern life\" and \"a really interesting way of communicating, personal but strange\".<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\n''[[V (American magazine)|V Magazine]]'' listed Poppy as part of the new generation of music, saying that \"...her hatched-from-an-egg, [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glenda the Good Witch]] vibes have inspired labels from 'human ASMR' to a one-woman 'digital rabbit hole', none of which seem to stick\".<ref name=\"vmag\">{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Samuel |title=The New Generation in Music|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/new-generation-music/ |website=V Magazine|accessdate=January 23, 2019|date=January 17, 2019 }}</ref> ''[[Paper Magazine|Paper]]'' magazine also listed Poppy as one of the 100 women revolutionizing pop music, noting that \"no matter what Poppy does, we can learn to expect the unexpected.\"<ref name=\"papermag\">{{cite web|last=Love Michael |first=Michael |title=100 Women Revolutionizing Pop|url=http://www.papermag.com/100-women-in-pop-2587872427.html?rebelltitem=65 |website=Paper Magazine|accessdate=January 23, 2019|date=July 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPoppy has spoken in interviews about her gender identity, saying \"I haven't figured it out, but I'd like to stay gender neutral. I don't want to classify myself. I'm just Poppy.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Her [[Questioning (sexuality and gender)|gender questioning]] influenced the themes of ''[[Am I a Girl?]]''. In a 2019 interview, she revealed that she identified as a girl, and said that she thinks \"everyone should be able to identify with whatever they choose\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flaunt.com/content/poppy|title=Poppy &#124; If Identity Is Currency, Let's Bet The Whole Damned Farm|website=Flaunt Magazine}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Films\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n|2019\n|''A Jester's Tale''\n|Herself\n|For the 2019 Sundance Film Festival.\n|}\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|''Jessie'']]\n|Student\n|Uncredited [[Cameo appearance|cameo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thefutoncritic.com/showatch/jessie/listings|title=Shows A-Z - jessie on disney {{!}} TheFutonCritic.com|website=thefutoncritic.com|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Impulse (TV series)|Impulse]]''\n| Poetry Student\n| Cameo<ref>{{cite web|title=Poppy appears in season 2 of the YouTube Originals series \"Impulse\" |url=https://twitter.com/PoppyUpdate/status/1184634778114543616|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Web===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Web\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Everybody Wants to Be Poppy''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Herself\n| Lead vocal role; 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Internet Famous with Poppy''\n| Lead role; 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[I'm Poppy]]''\n| Lead role<ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Poppy is as weird as its namesake YouTube star, but less intriguing|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/24/16928014/im-poppy-titanic-sinclair-youtube-red-review-sundance-2018|website=The Verge|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127083930/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/24/16928014/im-poppy-titanic-sinclair-youtube-red-review-sundance-2018|archivedate=January 27, 2018|date=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Poppy discography}}\n\n* ''[[Poppy.Computer]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Am I a Girl?]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[I Disagree]]'' (2020)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Gospel Of Poppy'' (2017)\n* ''Genesis One'' (2019)\n* ''Damnation: Poppy's Inferno'' (2020)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Headlining'''\n* [[Poppy.Computer Tour]] (2017\u201318)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/10/06/poppy-debut-album-poppy-computer-tour/ |title=Viral Musician Poppy Releases Debut Album, Will Embark on First-Ever Tour |last=Weiss |first=Geoff |date=October 6, 2017 |website=[[Tubefilter]] |accessdate=November 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034904/http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/10/06/poppy-debut-album-poppy-computer-tour/ |archivedate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Am I a Girl? Tour]] (2018\u201319)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://poppy.church/box-office |accessdate=July 10, 2018|title=Poppy.Church Box Office}}</ref>\n* I Disagree Tour (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/poppy/status/1181856915116187648|title=I Disagree Tour - Europe 2020 : On Sale Friday 10AM BST / 11AM CESTpic.twitter.com/VTthGG4QoY|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Co-headlining'''\n* Threesome Tour (2019; with [[Bring Me the Horizon]] and [[Sleeping with Sirens]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://loudwire.com/bring-me-the-horizon-fall-2019-tour-sleeping-with-sirens-poppy/|accessdate=August 8, 2019|title=Threesome Tour}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2016\n| 19 Under 19 Awards\n| Most Influential Song<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7503419/daya-shawn-mendes-tiger-beat-19-under-19|title=Daya, Shawn Mendes & More Nominated for Tiger Beat's 19 Under 19|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| \"Lowlife\"\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2017\n| [[Streamy Awards]]\n| Breakthrough Artist\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Herself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| WOWie Awards\n| Best YouTube Channel<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WorldOfWonder/status/931570205830066178|title=Poppy nominated for Best YouTube Channel|publisher=[[World of Wonder (production company)|World of Wonder]]|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Unicorn Awards\n| Iconic Moment of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|title=Poppy Unicorn Awards Iconic Moment of the Year|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|date=December 16, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216091636/http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|archivedate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|title=Poppy Unicorn Awards Song of the Year|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|date=December 16, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216091636/http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/results-youtuber-of-the-year-awards-2015/|archivedate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n| \"Computer Boy\"\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Best in Weird<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/10th/poppy|title=Poppy Shorty Awards Best in Weird|publisher=[[Shorty Awards]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 16, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190546/http://shortyawards.com/10th/poppy|archivedate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://impoppy.com/}}\n* {{imdb name|8824909}}\n* [http://www.businessinsider.com/poppy-youtube-religion-2017-11 ''Business Insider'' article, December 5, 2017]\n\n{{Poppy|state=expanded}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poppy}}\n[[Category:Poppy (singer)| ]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Ambient composers]]\n[[Category:Ambient musicians]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Electropop musicians]]\n[[Category:Female YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Music YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mad Decent artists]]\n[[Category:American religious leaders]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:American female heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Nu metal singers]]\n[[Category:Kawaii metal musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrimes(link changed toGrimes (musician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poppy_(entertainer)"}
{"title_page": "4AD", "text_new": "{{About||the year|AD 4|the Bauhaus EP|4AD (EP)}}\n{{More citations needed|date = January 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = 4AD\n| image       = 4AD record label logo.svg\n| image_bg    =\n| parent      = [[Beggars Group]]\n| founded     = 1980\n| founder     = [[Ivo Watts-Russell]]<br />Peter Kent\n| genre       = [[Alternative rock]], [[post-punk]], [[dream pop]], [[electronic music|electronic]], [[experimental music|experimental]]\n| defunct     =\n| distributor = [[Beggars Group]]\n| country     = United Kingdom\n| location    = [[London]]\n| url         = {{url|www.4ad.com}}\n}}\n\n'''4AD''' is a British [[independent record label]], founded by [[Ivo Watts-Russell]] and Peter Kent in 1980.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.facebook.com/fourad/about/\n| title=4AD \u2013 About\n| publisher=[[Facebook]]\n| accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref> It was originally funded by, and an imprint of, [[Beggars Banquet Records|Beggars Banquet]].<ref>{{cite news\n| last1 = Aston\n| first1 = Martin\n| title = 4AD: the 'pure' label behind Pixies and Cocteau Twins\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/10/4ad-label-behind-pixies-cocteau-twins\n| date = 2013-10-10\n| work = [[The Guardian]]\n| accessdate = 2017-01-14}}</ref>\n\nThe label gained prominence in the 1980s for releasing albums from [[alternative rock]], [[post-punk]], [[gothic rock]] and [[dream pop]] artists, such as [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], [[Cocteau Twins]], [[Modern English (band)|Modern English]], [[Dead Can Dance]], [[Clan of Xymox]], [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Throwing Muses]] and Watts-Russell's own musical project [[This Mortal Coil]]. In 1987, the label scored an international hit with the [[dance music]] single \"[[Pump Up the Volume (song)|Pump Up the Volume]]\" by the one-off project [[MARRS|M/A/R/R/S]]. 4AD continued to have success in the 1990s and 2000s with releases from [[The Breeders]], [[Lush (band)|Lush]], [[Red House Painters]], [[Camera Obscura (band)|Camera Obscura]], [[TV on the Radio]], [[St. Vincent (musician)|St. Vincent]] and [[Bon Iver]]. The label's current roster includes acts such as [[The National (band)|The National]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], [[Beirut (band)|Beirut]], [[Daughter (band)|Daughter]], [[Deerhunter]], [[Big Thief]], [[Purity Ring (band)|Purity Ring]] and [[Future Islands]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/blog/post/allmusic-loves-4ad-records\n| title = AllMusic Loves 4AD Records\n| last = Jeffries\n| first = David\n| date = 2013-11-06\n| publisher = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 2017-01-14}}</ref>\n\n4AD now forms part of the [[Beggars Group]], along with fellow independent labels [[Matador Records|Matador]], [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]], [[XL Recordings|XL]] and XL imprint [[Young Turks (record label)|Young Turks]]. The label's history has been detailed by Martin Aston in the biography ''Facing The Other Way'', released in 2013.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/sep/12/facing-other-way-4ad-aston-review\n| title=Facing the Other Way: The Story of 4AD by Martin Aston \u2013 review\n| author=Dorian Lynskey\n| date=2013-09-12\n| publisher=The Guardian\n| accessdate = 2017-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Ivo Watts-Russell]] and Peter Kent, employees of the Beggars Banquet record store and label, founded Axis Records in late 1979 as a property of Beggars Banquet that was run by the two. After the first four Axis singles in early 1980, the name was changed when it became apparent that the name Axis was already being used by another music company. The solution to this problem came from a promotional flyer that they had printed to call attention to the new releases. The flyer's designer had added some typography that played on both the new year and the idea of progress:\n\n1980 FORWARD<br />\n1980 FWD<br />\n1984 AD<br />\n4AD\n\nScrambling for a new name, Ivo glanced at the flyer and suggested \"4AD.\" Peter Kent agreed, and, with that split-second decision, 4AD was named.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nAn initial idea for the label was that it would be a \"testing ground\" for Beggars Banquet; successful acts would graduate up to Beggars Banquet after a year at 4AD. The only band to follow this path would be [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], who were signed to Beggars Banquet in late 1980 before Ivo and Peter purchased the label outright.\n\nThe two were the sole owners for about a year. Kent sold his share to Watts-Russell at the end of 1981, and started a new Beggars Banquet subsidiary, [[Situation Two Records]]. Watts-Russell would maintain ownership of the label, and act as its president, until the late 1990s.\n\nWatts-Russell invited the graphic designer [Vaughan Oliver] and the photographer Nigel Grierson to create sleeve art for the label, and as a result, 4AD acquired a visually distinctive identity. Its artists, such as [[Cocteau Twins]] and [[Dead Can Dance]], developed cult followings in the mid-1980s, but 4AD continued to evolve, and, after signing [[Throwing Muses]] and [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], the label increasingly concentrated on underground American rock music. In 1983, 4AD had a minor hit in America with the [[Modern English (band)|Modern English]] single \"[[I Melt With You]]\". In 1987, 4AD had a UK number-one hit with the [[sound collage|collaged]] \"[[Pump up the Volume (song)|Pump up the Volume]]\" by [[MARRS|M{{pipe}}A{{pipe}}R{{pipe}}R{{pipe}}S]] (licensed to [[4th & B'way Records|4th & B'Way]]/Island Records in the US).\n\nIn the 1990s, 4AD established an office in [[Los Angeles]] and had success with bands such as [[The Breeders]], [[Red House Painters]], [[Unrest (band)|Unrest]] and [[His Name Is Alive]]. In 1999, Watts-Russell sold his share in 4AD back to the Beggars Group (as it had by then become), but the label continued to release music and add new artists to its roster.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/6music/events/1980/guide.shtml\n| title=6 Music \u2013 1980 Forward \u2013 25 Years of 4AD\n| publisher=[[BBC]]\n| date=2005-11-21\n| accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref>\n\nThe label's deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]] in the United States in 1992 would start the beginning of a new phase in 4AD history. New signings that year included American underground acts [[Kendra Smith]], [[Tarnation (band)|Tarnation]], [[Air Miami]] and [[The Amps]].\n\nSimon Halliday took control of the label at the end of 2007. Immediate successes were [[Bon Iver]]'s critically lauded debut [[For Emma, Forever Ago]] (CAD 2809) and [[Dear Science]] by Brooklyn's [[TV on the Radio]] (CAD 2821). In 2008, the Beggars Group re-aligned itself so that several labels, including Beggars Banquet itself, were folded up on to the 4AD label.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/apr/30/afarewelltobeggarsbanquets|title=A farewell to Beggars Banquet's indie charm|last=Swash|first=Rosie|date=2008-04-30|department=Music Blog|website=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News & Media|accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/50320-label-shuffle-4ad-absorbs-too-pure-beggars-banquet|title=Label Shuffle: 4AD Absorbs Too Pure, Beggars Banquet |last=Solarski|first=Matthew|date=2008-04-29|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|publisher=Pitchfork Media|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219062324/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/50320-label-shuffle-4ad-absorbs-too-pure-beggars-banquet|archivedate=2008-12-19|url-status=dead|accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref> Bands including [[The National (band)|The National]] were moved to 4AD as a part of this merger. 2009 saw the release, amongst others, of [[St. Vincent (musician)|St. Vincent]]'s second record [[Actor (album)|Actor]] (CAD 2919) and [[Camera Obscura (band)|Camera Obscura]]'s [[My Maudlin Career]], with 2010 bringing [[The National (band)|The National]]'s [[High Violet]] and acclaimed albums from [[Ariel Pink's Haunted Graffiti]], [[Blonde Redhead]] and [[Deerhunter (band)|Deerhunter]].\n\nIn the next three years, 4AD oversaw new releases from [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]], [[Bon Iver]], [[Iron & Wine]], and [[Tune-Yards]], whilst also expanded its roster with a number of beats and electronic acts<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.factmag.com/2012/08/07/4ad-boss-simon-halliday-on-living-with-the-labels-past-and-building-its-future/\n| title=4AD boss Simon Halliday on living with the label\u2019s past, and his vision for its future\n| author=Joe Muggs\n| date=2012-08-07\n| publisher=[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]]\n| accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref> in the shape of acts including [[Purity Ring (band)|Purity Ring]] and [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], with the latter releasing one of the best received albums of 2012. The latest signings to the label are bEEdEEgEE, of [[Gang Gang Dance]], [[Lo-Fang]], and British producer [[Sohn (musician)|SOHN]]. At the start of 2014, the label also announced the additions of [[Future Islands]] and Merchandise, followed by D.D Dumbo.\n\n2015 saw critically lauded releases by Deerhunter and Grimes, amongst others, with the following years seeing the label, and The National, land their first ever UK #1 record with [[Sleep Well Beast]].  Latest signings to the roster include Aldous Harding and British artist Pixx.\n\n== Distribution ==\nWhile 4AD did not handle any distribution outside the [[United Kingdom]] for many years, it had many willing distributors in many countries: [[Virgin Records]] for France, [[Nippon Columbia]] distributed much of the label in [[Japan]], while [[PolyGram]] subsidiary [[Vertigo Records]] released many of the label's records in [[Canada]]. The United States had always been a tough market for 4AD, even though its records sold well there as imports. Only a few of the label's acts had deals to license their recordings in the US, among various labels.\n\nIn 1992, Ivo signed a five-year distribution deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]] so that nearly all 4AD releases would be released in the United States. While this seemed to be a simple licensing deal, in reality executives from Warner Bros. took a lot of control during this period, as 4AD shifted focus to the US market, signing more American bands. While still president, it is clear that Ivo ceded some control during this period, and when the deal ended, he offered to sell the label back to Beggars Banquet. Dead Can Dance's oeuvre, however, stayed with Warner Bros. until the sale back to Beggars Group.\n\nThe deal with Beggars was completed by early 1999, and since then it has owned 4AD and its distribution worldwide. This led to many negotiations for the label's back catalogue, like getting back US distribution rights for the [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Dead Can Dance]], and [[Cocteau Twins]].\n\n== Artists ==\n\n=== Current ===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"3\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|- <!-- Table only gets ONE ROW -->\n| style=\"vertical-align:top; width:*;\"| <!-- New COL -->\n* [[Aldous Harding]]\n* [[Atlas Sound]]\n* [[Becky and the Birds]]\n* [[Beirut (band)|Beirut]]\n* [[Big Thief]]\n* [[Bing & Ruth]]\n* [[The Breeders]]\n* [[D.D Dumbo]]\n* [[Daughter (band)|Daughter]]\n* [[Deerhunter]]\n\n* [[Dry Cleaning]]\n* [[Efterklang]]\n* [[EL VY]]\n* [[Daughter (band)#Ex:Re|Ex:Re]]\n* [[Future Islands]]\n* [[Gang Gang Dance]]\n* [[Gene Clark]]\n* [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]]\n* [[Holly Herndon]]\n | style=\"vertical-align:top; width:*;\"| <!-- New COL -->\n* [[The Lemon Twigs]]\n* [[Methyl Ethel]]\n* [[The National (band)|The National]]\n* Pixx\n* [[Purity Ring (band)|Purity Ring]]\n* [[Sohn (musician)|SOHN]]\n* [[Spencer.]]\n* [[Tune-Yards]]\n* [[U.S. Girls]]\n* [[Velvet Negroni]]\n|}\n\n=== Former ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n* [[Air Miami]] (disbanded)\n* [[The Amps]] (disbanded)\n* [[Anni Rossi]] (active)\n* [[A.R. Kane]] (disbanded)\n* [[Ariel Pink]] (active)\n* [[Tom Baril]] (photographer published by 4AD)\n* [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]] (disbanded, reunion 2019)\n* [[Bearz]] (still active as a David Gunstone project c. 2019)\n* [[Belly (band)|Belly]] (active 2018)\n* [[Heidi Berry]] (inactive; currently a teacher)\n* [[Bettie Serveert]] (active)\n* [[The Big Pink]] (active)\n* [[The Birthday Party (band)|The Birthday Party]] (disbanded)\n* [[Frank Black]] (active)\n* [[Blonde Redhead]] (active)\n* [[Bon Iver]] (active)\n* [[Broken Records (band)|Broken Records]] (active)\n* [[Michael Brook]] (active)\n* [[Bulgarian State Television Female Vocal Choir|The Bulgarian State Television Female Vocal Choir]] (active)\n* [[Camera Obscura (band)|Camera Obscura]] (active)\n* [[Celebration (band)|Celebration]] (active)\n* [[Clan of Xymox]] (active)\n* [[Cocteau Twins]] (disbanded)\n* [[Colourbox]] (dissolved)\n* [[Air Cuba (band)|Cuba]] (a.k.a. Air Cuba) (disbanded)\n* [[Cupol]] (one-off collaboration)\n* [[C.V.O. (band)|C.V.O.]] (disbanded)\n* [[Dance Chapter]] (disbanded)\n* [[Dead Can Dance]] (active)\n* [[Department of Eagles]] (active)\n* [[Diana Gordon (singer)|Diana Gordon]] (active)\n* [[Dif Juz]] (dissolved)\n* [[Tanya Donelly]] (active) {{col-4}}\n* [[Electricity in Our Homes]] (active)\n* [[Frazier Chorus]] (dissolved)\n* [[Future of the Left]] (disbanded)\n* [[Lisa Germano]] (active)\n* [[Lisa Gerrard]] (active)\n* [[Lisa Gerrard]] & [[Pieter Bourke]]\n* [[B. C. Gilbert]] & [[Graham Lewis|G. Lewis]]\n* [[The Glee Club (band)|The Glee Club]] (disbanded)\n* [[Rachel Goswell]] (inactive until Slowdive reunion 2014)\n* [[GusGus]] (active)\n* [[Rene Halkett]] & [[David J]]\n* [[Neil Halstead]] (active)\n* [[The Happy Family (band)|The Happy Family]] (disbanded)\n* [[Tim Hecker]] (active)\n* [[Kristin Hersh]] (active)\n* [[His Name Is Alive]] (active)\n* [[The Hope Blister]] (disbanded)\n* [[Rowland S. Howard]] & [[Lydia Lunch]]\n* [[In Camera (band)|In Camera]] (disbanded)\n* [[Inc. (band)|Inc.]] (active)\n* [[Indians (musician)|Indians]] (active)\n* [[Insides (band)|Insides]] (active)\n* [[Iron & Wine]] (active)\n* [[It Hugs Back]] (active)\n* [[J\u00f3hann J\u00f3hannsson]] (deceased)\n* [[Matt Johnson (singer)|Matt Johnson]] (The The founder, released 1 solo LP in 1981)\n* [[Joker (musician)|Joker]] (active)\n* [[Lakuna]] (one-off project)\n* [[Mark Lanegan|Mark Lanegan Band]]\n* [[Last Dance (band)|Last Dance]] (disbanded)\n* [[The Late Cord]] (one-off, thus far, collaboration)\n* Liima (active)\n* [[Liquorice (band)|Liquorice]] (one-off, thus far, collaboration)\n* [[Lo-Fang]] (active)\n* LNZNDRF (one-off, thus far, collaboration)\n* [[Lydia Lunch]] (active){{col-4}}\n* [[Lush (band)|Lush]] (disbanded; active 2015-2016)\n* [[MARRS|M{{pipe}}A{{pipe}}R{{pipe}}R{{pipe}}S]] (dissolved)\n* [[Mass (band)|Mass]] (disbanded)\n* [[Merchandise]] (active)\n* [[Vinny Miller]] (active)\n* [[Minotaur Shock]] (active)\n* [[Modern English (band)|Modern English]] (active)\n* [[Magnetophone]] (active)\n* [[Mojave 3]] (on hiatus)\n* [[John Moreland]] (active)\n* [[The Mountain Goats]] (active)\n* [[My Captains]] (disbanded)\n* [[Colin Newman]] (active)\n* [[Pieter Nooten]]/[[Michael Brook]]\n* [[The Paladins]] (on hiatus)\n* [[Pale Saints]] (disbanded)\n* [[The Past 7 Days]] (disbanded)\n* [[Brendan Perry]] (active)\n* [[Piano Magic]] (disbanded)\n* [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] (active)\n* [[Emma Pollock]] (active)\n* [[Psychotik Tanks]] (disbanded)\n* [[Ra Ra Riot]] (one-off split single with [[Stornoway]])\n* [[Red Atkins]] (deceased)\n* [[Red House Painters]] (disbanded)\n* [[Rema-Rema]] (active, c.2014-2015)\n* [[Richenel]] (active)\n* [[Scheer (band)|Scheer]] (disbanded)\n* [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]] (deceased)\n* [[Serena-Maneesh]] (active)\n* [[Shox (band)|Shox]] (disbanded)\n* [[Kendra Smith]] (active c.2017-2018)\n* [[Sort Sol (band)|Sort Sol]] (active)\n* [[SpaceGhostPurrp]] (active){{col-4}}\n* [[Spasmodic Caress]] (disbanded)\n* [[Spirea X]] (disbanded)\n* [[Spoonfed Hybrid]] (disbanded)\n* 