{"title_page": "Latrell Mitchell", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Latrell Mitchell\n|fullname       = Latrell Mitchell\n|image          = Latrell Mitchell Roosters.jpg\n|imagesize      = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = Latrell Goolagong<br>{{birth date and age|1997|06|18|df=y}}<ref>[https://www.roosters.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/sydney-roosters/latrell-mitchell/ Sydney Roosters profile]</ref><ref name=\"Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/latrell-mitchell-canterbury-bulldogs-offer-sydney-roosters-nrl-signing-news/189nnejqdfrp51xx803fv3n3pp|title=Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star|publisher=Sporting News|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_place    = [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|189|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Weight         = {{convert|102|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|CE|FB|FE}}\n|club1          = [[Sydney Roosters]]\n|year1start     = 2016\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = 96\n|tries1         = 65\n|goals1         = 209\n|fieldgoals1    = 1\n|points1        = 679 \n|club2          = [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]]\n|year2start     = 2020\n|year2end       = present\n|appearances2   = 2\n|tries2         = 0\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 0\n|teamA          = {{nowrap|[[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]]}}\n|yearAstart     = 2017\n|yearAend       = 18\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 0\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 6\n|teamB          = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n|yearBstart     = 2018\n|yearBend       = 19\n|appearancesB   = 4\n|triesB         = 2\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 8\n|teamC          = [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearCstart     = 2018\n|yearCend       = 19\n|appearancesC   = 4\n|triesC         = 0\n|goalsC         = 6\n|fieldgoalsC    = 0\n|pointsC        = 12\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|title=Latrell Mitchell - Career Stats & Summary|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/latrell-mitchell/summary.html|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n|updated        = 10 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Latrell Mitchell''' (born '''Latrell Goolagong''' on 18 June 1997) is an Indigenous Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|ce|wg}} or {{rlp|fb}} for the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]], and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] at international level. \n\nHe has played for the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] and [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] in the [[State of Origin series]].\n\n==Background==\nLatrell Goolagong was born in [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], [[New South Wales]], Australia on 18 June 1997.<ref name=\"Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/latrell-mitchell-canterbury-bulldogs-offer-sydney-roosters-nrl-signing-news/189nnejqdfrp51xx803fv3n3pp|title=Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star|publisher=Sporting News|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMitchell played his junior rugby league for the Taree Red Rovers. Mitchell's older brother Shaquai also played in the Roosters under-20s.<ref>{{cite web|date=15 September 2015|title=Honours for Mitch Barnett and Latrell Mitchell|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/3352370/honours-for-mitch-barnett-and-latrell-mitchell/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Mitchell changed his surname to his father's during his early teens.<ref>{{cite news|first=Adrian|last=Proszenko|date=2 April 2016|title=Why Sydney Roosters fullback Latrell Mitchell changed his name|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/sin-bin/why-sydney-roosters-fullback-latrell-mitchell-changed-his-name-20160402-gnwo0b.html|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> He is the great nephew of former World No. 1 female tennis player [[Evonne Goolagong Cawley]], with whom he no longer keeps in contact.<ref>{{cite web|last=Matthey|first=James|date=7 April 2016|title=Evonne Goolagong Cawley snubbed Latrell Mitchell and his brother|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/sports-life/evonne-goolagong-cawley-snubbed-latrell-mitchell-and-his-brother/news-story/d64de7add55f79f625c42652938e283b|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early career===\nIn 2013 and 2014, Mitchell played for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] under-16s and under-18s teams respectively.<ref>{{cite web|date=11 June 2014|title=Taree's Latrell Mitchell in NSW U18 origin side|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2343775/tarees-latrell-mitchell-in-nsw-u18-origin-side/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Mitchell played for the Roosters' [[S. G. Ball Cup]] team during the 2014 season, where he was named as the SG Ball Player of the Year, and the man-of-the-match in the SG Ball Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|date=16 June 2015|title=Roosters re-sign up-and-coming Juniors|url=http://www.roosters.com.au/news/2015/06/16/roosters_re_sign_up_.html|publisher=roosters.com.au|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> \n[[File:Latrell Mitchell.jpg|thumb|left|Mitchell playing for the [[Australian Schoolboys rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]]]]\nIn November 2014, Mitchell was selected for the [[Australian Schoolboys rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]] team for their tour of England and France.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonald|first=Mick|date=4 November 2014|title=Taree rugby league player in Australian Schoolboys side|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2674554/taree-rugby-league-player-in-australian-schoolboys-side/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> He was named as player of the series, having scored 13 tries in 7 games.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonald|first=Mick|date=1 January 2015|title=Taree's Latrell Mitchell named player of the Australian Schoolboys rugby league tour|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2794100/tarees-latrell-mitchell-named-player-of-the-australian-schoolboys-rugby-league-tour/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hooper|first=James|date=19 February 2015|title=Roosters discover next big thing, 17-year-old fullback Latrell Mitchell|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/sport-confidential-roosters-discover-next-big-thing-17yearold-fullback-latrell-mitchell/news-story/6618bfda16259f0777c42462c837b4da|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nMitchell played in the Roosters' [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team during the 2015 season. On 16 June 2015, he re-signed with the club until the end of the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite news|date=16 June 2015|title=Roosters re-sign Latrell Mitchell until 2019 as club prepares for life without Roger Tuivasa-Sheck|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/roosters/roosters-resign-latrell-mitchell-until-2019-as-club-prepares-for-life-without-roger-tuivasasheck/news-story/e29e31b2e2dcf4b7d94b68347e7e61f9|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> On 8 July 2015, Mitchell played for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] under 20s team where he played at fullback and scored a try in the 32-16 win at [[Lang Park|Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Webeck|first=Tony|date=8 July 2016|title=Kelly scores four as Blues win 20s|url=http://www.nrl.com/kelly-scores-four-as-blues-win-20s/tabid/10874/newsid/87757/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> On 14 September 2015, Mitchell was named on the interchange bench in the 2015 NYC Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 September 2015|title=2015 Holden Cup Team of the Year|url=http://www.nrl.com/2015-holden-cup-team-of-the-year/tabid/10874/newsid/89792/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nLatrell was named in the Roosters' [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|date=5 February 2016|title=Auckland Nines players to watch; Latrell Mitchell, Matt Parcell, Shannon Walker|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/ten-players-to-watch-at-auckland-nines/news-story/32563e05c7590d82347a756d7bd5b582|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> During the tournament, he scored 4 tries in 3 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/skys-the-limit-for-latrell-mitchell/tabid/10874/newsid/94135/default.aspx|title=Sky's the limit for Latrell Mitchell|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref> Mitchell also played in the Roosters' [[2016 World Club Series]] win against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]].<ref>{{cite web|date=19 February 2016|title=Latrell Mitchell earns lavish praise from Andrew Johns after starring role against St Helens|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/roosters/video-latrell-mitchell-earns-lavish-praise-from-andrew-johns-after-starring-role-against-st-helens/news-story/4360ac17b8f2f0b2dda51161e68852bc|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> In Round 1 of the [[2016 NRL season]], he made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the Roosters against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]].<ref>{{cite web|date=7 March 2016|title=Updated: Round 1 NRL team lists|url=http://www.nrl.com/updated-round-1-nrl-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/93308/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Mitchell played in every game for the Roosters during the season, finishing with 14 tries as the team's leading try scorer and leading point scorer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gabor|first=Martin|date=8 September 2016|title=Top 10 rookies of the year|url=https://www.nrl.com/top-10-rookies-of-the-year/tabid/10874/newsid/101033/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn the first round of the season, he scored a hat-trick in the Roosters' 32\u201318 win over the [[Gold Coast Titans]] at [[Robina Stadium]]. He has helped the Roosters climb up the ladder to 2nd place after 26 rounds scoring plenty of tries. He scored the game-winning try in week 1 of the 2017 finals against the Broncos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/live-nrl-gold-coast-titans-v-sydney-roosters-at-cbus-super-stadium/news-story/ae2ad9af95df5f906216f2849f66260b|title=NRL scores: Luke Keary, Mitchell Pearce lead Roosters win over Titans|work=Fox Sports|date=4 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> In the preliminary final against North Queensland, Mitchell endured a horror night which involved him sending two kick off restarts out on the full which both led to tries for the opposition.  Easts lost the match 29-16 in what proved to be one of the upsets of the season.<ref>https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/trent-robinson-throws-support-behind-roosters-star-latrell-mitchell-after-forgettable-saturday-night/news-story/7bc2827c13652cd5dcaa2581c47b01d7</ref><ref>http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4944105/north-queensland-cowboys-defy-odds-to-beat-sydney-roosters/?cs=2452</ref>\n\n===2018===\nAfter a good start to the season, Mitchell was selected to play for New South Wales in The [[2018 State of Origin series]] by coach [[Brad Fittler]]. He scored a try in the first match of the series.<ref>https://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/5436047/boyd-cordner-and-latrell-mitchell-tarees-two-true-blues/</ref>  Mitchell went on to play in the other 2 games of the series where New South Wales emerged victorious winning their first Origin shield since 2014.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/04/nsw-blues-utility-tyrone-peachey-explains-his-latrell-mitchell-moment/</ref>\nIn the 2018 finals series, Mitchell was handed a one match suspension after being charged for a crusher tackle on [[Josh Dugan]] in the Roosters victory over Cronulla.  Mitchell subsequently missed the preliminary final victory over Souths. On 30 September, Mitchell played in the [[2018 NRL Grand Final]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]] scoring a try and kicking four goals in the Sydney Roosters 21-6 win.<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-nrl-grand-final-2018-storm-vs-roosters-from-anz-stadium/news-story/201676e5e809c4713bcd150d9d0687da</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/latrell-mitchell-joins-an-infamous-list-of-finals-suspensions/news-story/6175c4f196d48992ba702c8d42ae6872</ref>\n\nAt the [[National Dreamtime Awards 2018]] Mitchell was named Male Sportsperson of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/sites/default/files/docs/digitised_collections/the_koori_mail/m0010050i690r.pdf|title=Dream of love, and success will come (pp32-34)|website=AIATSIS - The Koori Mail|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn round 6 of the [[2019 NRL season]], Mitchell scored a try and kicked the winning field goal as the [[Sydney Roosters]] defeated Melbourne 21-20 in golden point extra time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-s-boot-floors-storm-in-golden-point-classic-20190419-p51fqf.html/|title=Mitchell's boot floors Storm in golden-point classic|website=www.smh.com.au}}</ref> In round 8, Mitchell scored a hat-trick and kicked 7 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] defeated [[Wests Tigers]] 42-12 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-05-04/nrl-raiders-panthers-sea-eagles-bulldogs-roosters-wests-tigers/11062620/|title=Roosters thrash Tigers 42-12, Raiders beat Panthers 30-12, Sea Eagles defeat Bulldogs 18-10|website=www.abc.net.au}}</ref>\n\nBefore the start of the [[2019 State of Origin series]], Mitchell declared he would not sing the [[Australian National Anthem]], saying it didn't represent [[Aboriginal Australians]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Indigenous submission expected by NRL on national anthem boycott|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/dec/11/indigenous-submission-expected-by-nrl-on-national-anthem-boycott|work=Australian Associated Press|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\nAfter playing in the first game of the [[2019 State of Origin series]], he was dropped for the second.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/16/state-of-origin-game-two-teams |title=Latrell Mitchell dumped as NSW make seven changes for State of Origin Game 2|newspaper=[[The Guardian|Guardian]] |date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\nIn round 14 against Canterbury-Bankstown, Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 5 goals in a 38-12 victory at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/latrell-out-of-blues-despite-double-in-roosters-win-20190616-p51y8q.html/|title=Mitchell's double not enough to escape blues axe|website=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\nIn round 18 against Newcastle, Mitchell scored a try and kicked 8 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 48-10 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nrl/story/_/id/27226078/nrl-sydney-roosters-thrash-newcastle-knights-lose-jake-friend/|title=Sydney Roosters thrash Newcastle Knights, lose Jake Friend|website=ESPN}}</ref>\nIn Round 20 against the Gold Coast, Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 9 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 58-6 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/08/04/brett-morris-racks-up-try-150-as-roosters-outclass-titans/|title=Horror show for Holbrook as Roosters run riot|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\nIn round 22 against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 5 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 42-6 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-stars-as-roosters-thump-hapless-warriors-20190818-p52ia7.html/|title=Mitchell stars as Roosters thump hapless Warriors|website=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\nOn 2 October, Mitchell was named as the Dally M centre of the year at the [[Dally M Awards]] ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/10/02/dally-m-awards-2019-best-of-the-best/|title=Tedesco tops list of 2019 Dally M award winners|website=NRL}}</ref>\nMitchell played at centre in the club's [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] victory over the [[Canberra Raiders]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].  Mitchell was involved in the play which won the match as he threw a flick pass for [[Daniel Tupou]] who beat the Canberra defence and then passed back on the inside for [[James Tedesco]] to seal the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October, Mitchell was named in the Australian side for the upcoming [[2019 Oceania Cup|Oceania Cup]] fixtures.\n\n===2020===\nOn January 10, Mitchell announced on social media that he was departing the [[Sydney Roosters]] before the [[2020 NRL season]]. On January 13, Mitchell signed with [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]] on a one-year deal worth a reported $600,000 for the season with the option of extending for another year in 2021.  The contract signing ended months of speculation as in late 2019, Mitchell rejected an $800,000 a year offer to stay with the [[Sydney Roosters]].  It was then reported [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] and [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]] were interested in Mitchell's services but both clubs never officially offered any deal.  \n\nThe next club to offer Mitchell a contract were the [[Wests Tigers]] who reportedly offered Mitchell a four-year contract worth $1.2 million a season but this offer was turned down in favour of the move to South Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/latrell-mitchell-officially-signs-with-south-sydney/news-story/d9f6910610e5c95050403d5978bcc7d3/|title=Latrell Mitchell officially signs with South Sydney|website=www.news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/nrl-2020-latrell-mitchell-sydney-roosters-south-sydney-rabbitohs/rc2ajbjc4yr01lh9yi2jgnvfc/|title=Sydney Roosters release Latrell Mitchell from contract|website=Sporting News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/01/13/rabbitohs-announce-latrell-mitchell-signing-for-2020/|title=With Latrell deal done, Rabbitohs target Arrow|website=www.nrl.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, Mitchell spoke to the media about his rumoured move to [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] saying that he only went to Townsville for a holiday.  Mitchell went on to say \u201cNo, I just enjoyed the fishing, that\u2019s all it was, I only went for a holiday.  It\u2019s good country up there but too hot for me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/nrl-2020-latrell-mitchell-vs-cowboys-contract-paul-green-south-sydney-rabbitohs-rugby-league/news-story/9bc0a459883c64b837a96188b29617f4/|title=Gone fishing: Latrell Mitchell says Cowboys recruitment trip was \u2018just a holiday\u2019|website=www.foxsports.com.au}}</ref>\n\nMitchell made his debut for South Sydney in round 1 of the [[2020 NRL season]] against Cronulla-Sutherland.  South Sydney would go on to win the game 22-18, however Mitchell was benched by coach Wayne Bennett after just 55 minutes of play.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/rabbitohs/latrell-mitchell-benched-in-bunnies-debut-and-these-are-his-stats-at-fullback/news-story/3ca1e72fbd6b7e8a690c68d9ec1a85df/|title=Latrell Mitchell benched in Souths debut|website=www.foxsports.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.roosters.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/sydney-roosters/latrell-mitchell/ Sydney Roosters profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/13/playerid/6939/seasonid/45/default.aspx NRL profile]\n\n{{South Sydney Rabbitohs squad}}\n{{Sydney Roosters 2017 Auckland Nines Champions}}\n{{Sydney Roosters squad - 2018 NRL premiers}}\n{{Sydney Roosters squad - 2019 NRL Grand Final winners}}\n{{2015 National Youth Competition Team of the Year}}\n{{National Rugby League top points scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Latrell}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous All Stars players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Sydney Roosters players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n[[Category:Rugby league wingers]]\n[[Category:Rugby league fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Latrell Mitchell\n|fullname       = Latrell Mitchell\n|image          = Latrell Mitchell Roosters.jpg\n|imagesize      = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = Latrell Goolagong<br>{{birth date and age|1997|06|18|df=y}}<ref>[https://www.roosters.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/sydney-roosters/latrell-mitchell/ Sydney Roosters profile]</ref><ref name=\"Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/latrell-mitchell-canterbury-bulldogs-offer-sydney-roosters-nrl-signing-news/189nnejqdfrp51xx803fv3n3pp|title=Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star|publisher=Sporting News|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_place    = [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n|height         = {{convert|193|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Weight         = {{convert|102|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|CE|FB|FE}}\n|club1          = [[Sydney Roosters]]\n|year1start     = 2016\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = 96\n|tries1         = 65\n|goals1         = 209\n|fieldgoals1    = 1\n|points1        = 679 \n|club2          = [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]]\n|year2start     = 2020\n|year2end       = present\n|appearances2   = 2\n|tries2         = 0\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 0\n|teamA          = {{nowrap|[[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]]}}\n|yearAstart     = 2017\n|yearAend       = 18\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 0\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 6\n|teamB          = [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]]\n|yearBstart     = 2018\n|yearBend       = 19\n|appearancesB   = 4\n|triesB         = 2\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 8\n|teamC          = [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]]\n|yearCstart     = 2018\n|yearCend       = 19\n|appearancesC   = 4\n|triesC         = 0\n|goalsC         = 6\n|fieldgoalsC    = 0\n|pointsC        = 12\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|title=Latrell Mitchell - Career Stats & Summary|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/latrell-mitchell/summary.html|publisher=Rugby League Project|accessdate=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n|updated        = 10 November 2019\n}}\n\n'''Latrell Mitchell''' (born '''Latrell Goolagong''' on 18 June 1997) is an Indigenous Australian professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|ce|wg}} or {{rlp|fb}} for the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]], and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] at international level. \n\nHe has played for the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] and [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] in the [[State of Origin series]].\n\n==Background==\nLatrell Goolagong was born in [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], [[New South Wales]], Australia on 18 June 1997.<ref name=\"Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/latrell-mitchell-canterbury-bulldogs-offer-sydney-roosters-nrl-signing-news/189nnejqdfrp51xx803fv3n3pp|title=Latrell Mitchell: Canterbury Bulldogs set to make record offer to Roosters star|publisher=Sporting News|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMitchell played his junior rugby league for the Taree Red Rovers. Mitchell's older brother Shaquai also played in the Roosters under-20s.<ref>{{cite web|date=15 September 2015|title=Honours for Mitch Barnett and Latrell Mitchell|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/3352370/honours-for-mitch-barnett-and-latrell-mitchell/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Mitchell changed his surname to his father's during his early teens.<ref>{{cite news|first=Adrian|last=Proszenko|date=2 April 2016|title=Why Sydney Roosters fullback Latrell Mitchell changed his name|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/sin-bin/why-sydney-roosters-fullback-latrell-mitchell-changed-his-name-20160402-gnwo0b.html|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> He is the great nephew of former World No. 1 female tennis player [[Evonne Goolagong Cawley]], with whom he no longer keeps in contact.<ref>{{cite web|last=Matthey|first=James|date=7 April 2016|title=Evonne Goolagong Cawley snubbed Latrell Mitchell and his brother|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/sports-life/evonne-goolagong-cawley-snubbed-latrell-mitchell-and-his-brother/news-story/d64de7add55f79f625c42652938e283b|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early career===\nIn 2013 and 2014, Mitchell played for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] under-16s and under-18s teams respectively.<ref>{{cite web|date=11 June 2014|title=Taree's Latrell Mitchell in NSW U18 origin side|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2343775/tarees-latrell-mitchell-in-nsw-u18-origin-side/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Mitchell played for the Roosters' [[S. G. Ball Cup]] team during the 2014 season, where he was named as the SG Ball Player of the Year, and the man-of-the-match in the SG Ball Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|date=16 June 2015|title=Roosters re-sign up-and-coming Juniors|url=http://www.roosters.com.au/news/2015/06/16/roosters_re_sign_up_.html|publisher=roosters.com.au|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> \n[[File:Latrell Mitchell.jpg|thumb|left|Mitchell playing for the [[Australian Schoolboys rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]]]]\nIn November 2014, Mitchell was selected for the [[Australian Schoolboys rugby league team|Australian Schoolboys]] team for their tour of England and France.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonald|first=Mick|date=4 November 2014|title=Taree rugby league player in Australian Schoolboys side|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2674554/taree-rugby-league-player-in-australian-schoolboys-side/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> He was named as player of the series, having scored 13 tries in 7 games.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonald|first=Mick|date=1 January 2015|title=Taree's Latrell Mitchell named player of the Australian Schoolboys rugby league tour|url=http://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/2794100/tarees-latrell-mitchell-named-player-of-the-australian-schoolboys-rugby-league-tour/|publisher=Manning River Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hooper|first=James|date=19 February 2015|title=Roosters discover next big thing, 17-year-old fullback Latrell Mitchell|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/sport-confidential-roosters-discover-next-big-thing-17yearold-fullback-latrell-mitchell/news-story/6618bfda16259f0777c42462c837b4da|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nMitchell played in the Roosters' [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team during the 2015 season. On 16 June 2015, he re-signed with the club until the end of the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite news|date=16 June 2015|title=Roosters re-sign Latrell Mitchell until 2019 as club prepares for life without Roger Tuivasa-Sheck|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/roosters/roosters-resign-latrell-mitchell-until-2019-as-club-prepares-for-life-without-roger-tuivasasheck/news-story/e29e31b2e2dcf4b7d94b68347e7e61f9|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> On 8 July 2015, Mitchell played for the [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] under 20s team where he played at fullback and scored a try in the 32-16 win at [[Lang Park|Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Webeck|first=Tony|date=8 July 2016|title=Kelly scores four as Blues win 20s|url=http://www.nrl.com/kelly-scores-four-as-blues-win-20s/tabid/10874/newsid/87757/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> On 14 September 2015, Mitchell was named on the interchange bench in the 2015 NYC Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 September 2015|title=2015 Holden Cup Team of the Year|url=http://www.nrl.com/2015-holden-cup-team-of-the-year/tabid/10874/newsid/89792/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nLatrell was named in the Roosters' [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|date=5 February 2016|title=Auckland Nines players to watch; Latrell Mitchell, Matt Parcell, Shannon Walker|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/ten-players-to-watch-at-auckland-nines/news-story/32563e05c7590d82347a756d7bd5b582|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> During the tournament, he scored 4 tries in 3 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/skys-the-limit-for-latrell-mitchell/tabid/10874/newsid/94135/default.aspx|title=Sky's the limit for Latrell Mitchell|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref> Mitchell also played in the Roosters' [[2016 World Club Series]] win against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]].<ref>{{cite web|date=19 February 2016|title=Latrell Mitchell earns lavish praise from Andrew Johns after starring role against St Helens|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/roosters/video-latrell-mitchell-earns-lavish-praise-from-andrew-johns-after-starring-role-against-st-helens/news-story/4360ac17b8f2f0b2dda51161e68852bc|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> In Round 1 of the [[2016 NRL season]], he made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the Roosters against the [[South Sydney Rabbitohs]].<ref>{{cite web|date=7 March 2016|title=Updated: Round 1 NRL team lists|url=http://www.nrl.com/updated-round-1-nrl-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/93308/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Mitchell played in every game for the Roosters during the season, finishing with 14 tries as the team's leading try scorer and leading point scorer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gabor|first=Martin|date=8 September 2016|title=Top 10 rookies of the year|url=https://www.nrl.com/top-10-rookies-of-the-year/tabid/10874/newsid/101033/default.aspx|publisher=NRL.com|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn the first round of the season, he scored a hat-trick in the Roosters' 32\u201318 win over the [[Gold Coast Titans]] at [[Robina Stadium]]. He has helped the Roosters climb up the ladder to 2nd place after 26 rounds scoring plenty of tries. He scored the game-winning try in week 1 of the 2017 finals against the Broncos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/live-nrl-gold-coast-titans-v-sydney-roosters-at-cbus-super-stadium/news-story/ae2ad9af95df5f906216f2849f66260b|title=NRL scores: Luke Keary, Mitchell Pearce lead Roosters win over Titans|work=Fox Sports|date=4 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> In the preliminary final against North Queensland, Mitchell endured a horror night which involved him sending two kick off restarts out on the full which both led to tries for the opposition.  Easts lost the match 29-16 in what proved to be one of the upsets of the season.<ref>https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/trent-robinson-throws-support-behind-roosters-star-latrell-mitchell-after-forgettable-saturday-night/news-story/7bc2827c13652cd5dcaa2581c47b01d7</ref><ref>http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4944105/north-queensland-cowboys-defy-odds-to-beat-sydney-roosters/?cs=2452</ref>\n\n===2018===\nAfter a good start to the season, Mitchell was selected to play for New South Wales in The [[2018 State of Origin series]] by coach [[Brad Fittler]]. He scored a try in the first match of the series.<ref>https://www.manningrivertimes.com.au/story/5436047/boyd-cordner-and-latrell-mitchell-tarees-two-true-blues/</ref>  Mitchell went on to play in the other 2 games of the series where New South Wales emerged victorious winning their first Origin shield since 2014.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/07/04/nsw-blues-utility-tyrone-peachey-explains-his-latrell-mitchell-moment/</ref>\nIn the 2018 finals series, Mitchell was handed a one match suspension after being charged for a crusher tackle on [[Josh Dugan]] in the Roosters victory over Cronulla.  Mitchell subsequently missed the preliminary final victory over Souths. On 30 September, Mitchell played in the [[2018 NRL Grand Final]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]] scoring a try and kicking four goals in the Sydney Roosters 21-6 win.<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/live-nrl-grand-final-2018-storm-vs-roosters-from-anz-stadium/news-story/201676e5e809c4713bcd150d9d0687da</ref><ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/latrell-mitchell-joins-an-infamous-list-of-finals-suspensions/news-story/6175c4f196d48992ba702c8d42ae6872</ref>\n\nAt the [[National Dreamtime Awards 2018]] Mitchell was named Male Sportsperson of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/sites/default/files/docs/digitised_collections/the_koori_mail/m0010050i690r.pdf|title=Dream of love, and success will come (pp32-34)|website=AIATSIS - The Koori Mail|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn round 6 of the [[2019 NRL season]], Mitchell scored a try and kicked the winning field goal as the [[Sydney Roosters]] defeated Melbourne 21-20 in golden point extra time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-s-boot-floors-storm-in-golden-point-classic-20190419-p51fqf.html/|title=Mitchell's boot floors Storm in golden-point classic|website=www.smh.com.au}}</ref> In round 8, Mitchell scored a hat-trick and kicked 7 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] defeated [[Wests Tigers]] 42-12 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-05-04/nrl-raiders-panthers-sea-eagles-bulldogs-roosters-wests-tigers/11062620/|title=Roosters thrash Tigers 42-12, Raiders beat Panthers 30-12, Sea Eagles defeat Bulldogs 18-10|website=www.abc.net.au}}</ref>\n\nBefore the start of the [[2019 State of Origin series]], Mitchell declared he would not sing the [[Australian National Anthem]], saying it didn't represent [[Aboriginal Australians]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Indigenous submission expected by NRL on national anthem boycott|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/dec/11/indigenous-submission-expected-by-nrl-on-national-anthem-boycott|work=Australian Associated Press|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\nAfter playing in the first game of the [[2019 State of Origin series]], he was dropped for the second.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/16/state-of-origin-game-two-teams |title=Latrell Mitchell dumped as NSW make seven changes for State of Origin Game 2|newspaper=[[The Guardian|Guardian]] |date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\nIn round 14 against Canterbury-Bankstown, Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 5 goals in a 38-12 victory at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/latrell-out-of-blues-despite-double-in-roosters-win-20190616-p51y8q.html/|title=Mitchell's double not enough to escape blues axe|website=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\nIn round 18 against Newcastle, Mitchell scored a try and kicked 8 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 48-10 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nrl/story/_/id/27226078/nrl-sydney-roosters-thrash-newcastle-knights-lose-jake-friend/|title=Sydney Roosters thrash Newcastle Knights, lose Jake Friend|website=ESPN}}</ref>\nIn Round 20 against the Gold Coast, Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 9 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 58-6 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/08/04/brett-morris-racks-up-try-150-as-roosters-outclass-titans/|title=Horror show for Holbrook as Roosters run riot|website=NRL}}</ref>\n\nIn round 22 against the [[New Zealand Warriors]], Mitchell scored 2 tries and kicked 5 goals as the [[Sydney Roosters]] won the match 42-6 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/mitchell-stars-as-roosters-thump-hapless-warriors-20190818-p52ia7.html/|title=Mitchell stars as Roosters thump hapless Warriors|website=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\nOn 2 October, Mitchell was named as the Dally M centre of the year at the [[Dally M Awards]] ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/10/02/dally-m-awards-2019-best-of-the-best/|title=Tedesco tops list of 2019 Dally M award winners|website=NRL}}</ref>\nMitchell played at centre in the club's [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] victory over the [[Canberra Raiders]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].  Mitchell was involved in the play which won the match as he threw a flick pass for [[Daniel Tupou]] who beat the Canberra defence and then passed back on the inside for [[James Tedesco]] to seal the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October, Mitchell was named in the Australian side for the upcoming [[2019 Oceania Cup|Oceania Cup]] fixtures.\n\n===2020===\nOn January 10, Mitchell announced on social media that he was departing the [[Sydney Roosters]] before the [[2020 NRL season]]. On January 13, Mitchell signed with [[South Sydney Rabbitohs|South Sydney]] on a one-year deal worth a reported $600,000 for the season with the option of extending for another year in 2021.  The contract signing ended months of speculation as in late 2019, Mitchell rejected an $800,000 a year offer to stay with the [[Sydney Roosters]].  It was then reported [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] and [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury-Bankstown]] were interested in Mitchell's services but both clubs never officially offered any deal.  \n\nThe next club to offer Mitchell a contract were the [[Wests Tigers]] who reportedly offered Mitchell a four-year contract worth $1.2 million a season but this offer was turned down in favour of the move to South Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/latrell-mitchell-officially-signs-with-south-sydney/news-story/d9f6910610e5c95050403d5978bcc7d3/|title=Latrell Mitchell officially signs with South Sydney|website=www.news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/league/news/nrl-2020-latrell-mitchell-sydney-roosters-south-sydney-rabbitohs/rc2ajbjc4yr01lh9yi2jgnvfc/|title=Sydney Roosters release Latrell Mitchell from contract|website=Sporting News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/01/13/rabbitohs-announce-latrell-mitchell-signing-for-2020/|title=With Latrell deal done, Rabbitohs target Arrow|website=www.nrl.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, Mitchell spoke to the media about his rumoured move to [[North Queensland Cowboys|North Queensland]] saying that he only went to Townsville for a holiday.  Mitchell went on to say \u201cNo, I just enjoyed the fishing, that\u2019s all it was, I only went for a holiday.  It\u2019s good country up there but too hot for me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/nrl-2020-latrell-mitchell-vs-cowboys-contract-paul-green-south-sydney-rabbitohs-rugby-league/news-story/9bc0a459883c64b837a96188b29617f4/|title=Gone fishing: Latrell Mitchell says Cowboys recruitment trip was \u2018just a holiday\u2019|website=www.foxsports.com.au}}</ref>\n\nMitchell made his debut for South Sydney in round 1 of the [[2020 NRL season]] against Cronulla-Sutherland.  South Sydney would go on to win the game 22-18, however Mitchell was benched by coach Wayne Bennett after just 55 minutes of play.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/teams/rabbitohs/latrell-mitchell-benched-in-bunnies-debut-and-these-are-his-stats-at-fullback/news-story/3ca1e72fbd6b7e8a690c68d9ec1a85df/|title=Latrell Mitchell benched in Souths debut|website=www.foxsports.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.roosters.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/sydney-roosters/latrell-mitchell/ Sydney Roosters profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/13/playerid/6939/seasonid/45/default.aspx NRL profile]\n\n{{South Sydney Rabbitohs squad}}\n{{Sydney Roosters 2017 Auckland Nines Champions}}\n{{Sydney Roosters squad - 2018 NRL premiers}}\n{{Sydney Roosters squad - 2019 NRL Grand Final winners}}\n{{2015 National Youth Competition Team of the Year}}\n{{National Rugby League top points scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Latrell}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous All Stars players]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Rugby League State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Sydney Roosters players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n[[Category:Rugby league wingers]]\n[[Category:Rugby league fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:22c2:2401:702f:4713:2c7a:95c0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latrell_Mitchell"}
{"title_page": "Mental health during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{short description|Impact of the pandemic on the mental health of people around the world}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted the mental health of people around the world. The Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial Support recommends that the core principles of mental health support during an emergency are \"do no harm, promote human rights and equality, use participatory approaches, build on existing resources and capacities, adopt multi-layered interventions and work with integrated support systems.\"<ref name= iascg>{{cite web |title=Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial support |url=https://www.mhinnovation.net/sites/default/files/downloads/resource/IASC%20Interim%20Briefing%20Note%20on%20COVID-19%20Outbreak%20Readiness%20and%20Response%20Operations%20-%20MHPSS.pdf |publisher=MH Innovation |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Causes for mental health issues during COVID-19 pandemic==\nThe [[COVID-19]] pandemic can cause stress, anxiety and worry among individuals. Common causes of psychological stress during pandemics include, fear of falling ill and dying, avoiding health care due to fear of being infected while in care, fear of losing work and livelihoods, fear of being socially excluded, fear of being placed in quarantine, feeling of powerlessness in protecting oneself and loved ones, fear of being separated from loved ones and caregivers, refusal to care for vulnerable individuals due to fear of infection, feelings of helplessness, boredom, loneliness and depression due to being isolated and fear of re-living the experience of a previous pandemic.<ref name= iascg/> In addition to these problems, COVID-19 can cause additional psychological responses, such as, risk of being infected when the transmission mode of COVID-19 is not 100% clear, common symptoms of other health problems being mistaken for COVID-19, increased worry about children being at home alone (during school shutdowns etc.) while parents have to be at work and risk of deterioration of physical and mental health of vulnerable individuals if care support is not in place.<ref name= iascg/> Frontline workers, such as doctors and nurses may experience additional mental health problems. [[Stigmatization]] towards working with COVID-19 patients, stress from using strict biosecurity measures (such as physical strain of protective equipment, need for constant awareness and vigilance, strict procedures to follow, preventing autonomy, physical isolation making it difficult to provide comfort to the sick), higher demands in the work setting, reduced capacity to use social support due to physical distancing and stigma, insufficient capacity to give self-care, insufficient knowledge about the long-term exposure to individuals infected with COVID-19 and fear that they could pass infection to their loved ones can put frontline workers in additional stress.<ref name= iascg/><ref>{{cite web |title=ICN COVID-19 Update: New guidance on mental health and psychosocial support will help to alleviate effects of stress on hard-pressed staff |url=https://www.icn.ch/news/icn-covid-19-update-new-guidance-mental-health-and-psychosocial-support-will-help-alleviate |website=ICN - International Council of Nurses |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Emergency Responders: Tips for taking care of yourself |url=https://emergency.cdc.gov/coping/responders.asp |work=emergency.cdc.gov |date=10 January 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention and management of mental health conditions==\nThe [[World Health Organization]]  and the [[Centre for Disease Control]] have issued guidelines for preventing mental health issues during the COVID-19 pandemic. The summarized guidelines are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=Mental health and psychosocial considerations during the COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/mental-health-considerations.pdf |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prepare/managing-stress-anxiety.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===For general population<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dickerson |first1=Desiree |title=Seven tips to manage your mental health and well-being during the COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00933-5 |journal=Nature |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00933-5 |date=26 March 2020|pmid=32218548 }}</ref>===\n* Be empathetic to all the affected individuals, regardless of their nationality or ethnicity.\n* Use [[people-first language]] while describing individuals affected with COVID-19. \n* Minimize watching the news if that makes one anxious. Seek information only from trusted sources, preferably once or twice a day.\n* Protect yourself and be supportive to others, such as your neighbours.\n* Find opportunities to amplify positive stories of local people who have experienced COVID-19.\n* Honor healthcare workers who are supporting those affected with COVID-19.\n\n===For healthcare workers<ref>{{cite web |title=Moral distress can affect healthcare personnel during COVID-19 crisis {{!}} Karolinska Institutet Nyheter |url=https://news.ki.se/moral-distress-can-affect-healthcare-personnel-during-covid-19-crisis?_ga=2.213417492.1211327733.1585393496-2112856690.1585393496 |website=news.ki.se |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>===\n{{See also|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic-related shortages#Health workers}}\n* Feeling under pressure is normal during the times of a crisis. Managing one's mental health is as important as managing physical health.\n* Follow coping strategies, ensure sufficient rest eat good food, engage in physical activity, avoid using tobacco, alcohol or drugs. Use the coping strategies that have previously worked for you under stressful situations.\n* If one is experiencing avoidance by the family or the community, stay connected with loved ones, including digital methods.\n* Use understandable ways to share messages to people with disabilities.\n* Know how to link people affected with COVID-19 with available resources.\n\n===For team leaders in health facilities===\n* Keep all staff protected from poor mental health. Focus on long-term occupational capacity rather than short term results.\n* Ensure good quality communication and accurate updates.\n* Ensure that all staff are aware of where and how mental health support can accessed.\n* Orient all staff on how to provide psychological first aid to the affected.\n* Emergency mental health conditions should be managed in healthcare facilities.\n* Ensure availability of essential psychiatric medications at all levels of health care.\n\n===For carers of children===\n* Help children find positive ways to express their emotions.\n* Avoid separating children from their parents/carers as much as possible. Ensure that regular contact with parents and carers is maintained, should the child be placed in isolation.\n* Maintain family routines as much as possible and provide age-appropriate engaging activities for children.\n* Children might seek more attachment from parents, in which case, discuss about COVID-19 with them in an age-appropriate way.\n\n===For older adults, people with underlying health conditions and their carers===\n* Older adults, those especially in isolation or suffering from pre-existing neurological conditions, may become more anxious, angry or withdrawn. Provide practical and emotional support through caregivers and healthcare professionals.\n* Share simple facts on the crisis and give clear information about how to reduce the risk of infection. \n* Have access to all the medications that are currently being used.\n* Know in advance where and how to get practical help.\n* Learn and perform simple daily exercises to practice at home.\n* Keep regular schedules as much as possible and keep in touch with loved ones.\n\n===For people in isolation===\n* Stay connected and maintain social networks.\n* Pay attention to own needs and feelings. Engage in activities that you find relaxing.\n* Avoid listening to rumors that make you uncomfortable.\n\n==Long term consequences of COVID-19 pandemic on mental health==\nAccording to the Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial Support (IASC), there can be long term consequences due to the coronavirus pandemic. Deterioration of social networks and economies, stigma towards survivors of COVID-19, possible higher anger and aggression of frontline workers and the government, possible anger and aggression against children and possible mistrust of information provided by official authorities are some of the long term consequences anticipated by the IASC.<ref name= iascg/> Some of these consequences could be due to realistic dangers, but many reactions could be borne out of lack of knowledge, rumors and misinformation. It is also possible that some people may have positive experiences, such as pride about finding ways of coping. It is likely that community members show [[altruism]] and cooperation when faced with a crisis, and people might experience satisfaction from helping others.\n==Reports of mental health issues==\n* The state finance minister of Hesse, Germany, committed suicide possibly due to the mental stress from having to deal with the [[Financial_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|financial consequences of COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Welle (www.dw.com) |first1=Deutsche |title=German state finance minister Thomas Sch\u00e4fer found dead {{!}} DW {{!}} 29.03.2020 |url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-state-finance-minister-thomas-sch%C3%A4fer-found-dead/a-52948976 |work=DW.COM}}</ref>\n* There are reports of people committing suicide after not being able to access alcohol during the [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|lockdown associated with coronavirus pandemic in India]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two tipplers in Kerala commit suicide upset at not getting liquor during COVID-19 lockdown |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2020/mar/29/two-tipplers-in-kerala-commit-suicide-upset-at-not-getting-liquor-during-covid-19-lockdown-2123056.html |work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Mental health]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Impact of the pandemic on the mental health of people around the world}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted the mental health of people around the world. The Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial Support recommends that the core principles of mental health support during an emergency are \"do no harm, promote human rights and equality, use participatory approaches, build on existing resources and capacities, adopt multi-layered interventions and work with integrated support systems.\"<ref name= iascg>{{cite web |title=Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial support |url=https://www.mhinnovation.net/sites/default/files/downloads/resource/IASC%20Interim%20Briefing%20Note%20on%20COVID-19%20Outbreak%20Readiness%20and%20Response%20Operations%20-%20MHPSS.pdf |publisher=MH Innovation |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Causes for mental health issues during COVID-19 pandemic==\nThe [[COVID-19]] pandemic can cause stress, anxiety and worry among individuals. Common causes of psychological stress during pandemics include, fear of falling ill and dying, avoiding health care due to fear of being infected while in care, fear of losing work and livelihoods, fear of being socially excluded, fear of being placed in quarantine, feeling of powerlessness in protecting oneself and loved ones, fear of being separated from loved ones and caregivers, refusal to care for vulnerable individuals due to fear of infection, feelings of helplessness, boredom, loneliness and depression due to being isolated and fear of re-living the experience of a previous pandemic.<ref name= iascg/> In addition to these problems, COVID-19 can cause additional psychological responses, such as, risk of being infected when the transmission mode of COVID-19 is not 100% clear, common symptoms of other health problems being mistaken for COVID-19, increased worry about children being at home alone (during school shutdowns etc.) while parents have to be at work and risk of deterioration of physical and mental health of vulnerable individuals if care support is not in place.<ref name= iascg/> Frontline workers, such as doctors and nurses may experience additional mental health problems. [[Stigmatization]] towards working with COVID-19 patients, stress from using strict biosecurity measures (such as physical strain of protective equipment, need for constant awareness and vigilance, strict procedures to follow, preventing autonomy, physical isolation making it difficult to provide comfort to the sick), higher demands in the work setting, reduced capacity to use social support due to physical distancing and stigma, insufficient capacity to give self-care, insufficient knowledge about the long-term exposure to individuals infected with COVID-19 and fear that they could pass infection to their loved ones can put frontline workers in additional stress.<ref name= iascg/><ref>{{cite web |title=ICN COVID-19 Update: New guidance on mental health and psychosocial support will help to alleviate effects of stress on hard-pressed staff |url=https://www.icn.ch/news/icn-covid-19-update-new-guidance-mental-health-and-psychosocial-support-will-help-alleviate |website=ICN - International Council of Nurses |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Emergency Responders: Tips for taking care of yourself |url=https://emergency.cdc.gov/coping/responders.asp |work=emergency.cdc.gov |date=10 January 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention and management of mental health conditions==\nThe [[World Health Organization]]  and the [[Centre for Disease Control]] have issued guidelines for preventing mental health issues during the COVID-19 pandemic. The summarized guidelines are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=Mental health and psychosocial considerations during the COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/mental-health-considerations.pdf |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prepare/managing-stress-anxiety.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===For general population<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dickerson |first1=Desiree |title=Seven tips to manage your mental health and well-being during the COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00933-5 |journal=Nature |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00933-5 |date=26 March 2020|pmid=32218548 }}</ref>===\n* Be empathetic to all the affected individuals, regardless of their nationality or ethnicity.\n* Use [[people-first language]] while describing individuals affected with COVID-19. \n* Minimize watching the news if that makes one anxious. Seek information only from trusted sources, preferably once or twice a day.\n* Protect yourself and be supportive to others, such as your neighbours.\n* Find opportunities to amplify positive stories of local people who have experienced COVID-19.\n* Honor healthcare workers who are supporting those affected with COVID-19.\n\n===For healthcare workers<ref>{{cite web |title=Moral distress can affect healthcare personnel during COVID-19 crisis {{!}} Karolinska Institutet Nyheter |url=https://news.ki.se/moral-distress-can-affect-healthcare-personnel-during-covid-19-crisis?_ga=2.213417492.1211327733.1585393496-2112856690.1585393496 |website=news.ki.se |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>===\n{{See also|2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic_related_shortages#Health_workers}}\n* Feeling under pressure is normal during the times of a crisis. Managing one's mental health is as important as managing physical health.\n* Follow coping strategies, ensure sufficient rest eat good food, engage in physical activity, avoid using tobacco, alcohol or drugs. Use the coping strategies that have previously worked for you under stressful situations.\n* If one is experiencing avoidance by the family or the community, stay connected with loved ones, including digital methods.\n* Use understandable ways to share messages to people with disabilities.\n* Know how to link people affected with COVID-19 with available resources.\n\n===For team leaders in health facilities===\n* Keep all staff protected from poor mental health. Focus on long-term occupational capacity rather than short term results.\n* Ensure good quality communication and accurate updates.\n* Ensure that all staff are aware of where and how mental health support can accessed.\n* Orient all staff on how to provide psychological first aid to the affected.\n* Emergency mental health conditions should be managed in healthcare facilities.\n* Ensure availability of essential psychiatric medications at all levels of health care.\n\n===For carers of children===\n* Help children find positive ways to express their emotions.\n* Avoid separating children from their parents/carers as much as possible. Ensure that regular contact with parents and carers is maintained, should the child be placed in isolation.\n* Maintain family routines as much as possible and provide age-appropriate engaging activities for children.\n* Children might seek more attachment from parents, in which case, discuss about COVID-19 with them in an age-appropriate way.\n\n===For older adults, people with underlying health conditions and their carers===\n* Older adults, those especially in isolation or suffering from pre-existing neurological conditions, may become more anxious, angry or withdrawn. Provide practical and emotional support through caregivers and healthcare professionals.\n* Share simple facts on the crisis and give clear information about how to reduce the risk of infection. \n* Have access to all the medications that are currently being used.\n* Know in advance where and how to get practical help.\n* Learn and perform simple daily exercises to practice at home.\n* Keep regular schedules as much as possible and keep in touch with loved ones.\n\n===For people in isolation===\n* Stay connected and maintain social networks.\n* Pay attention to own needs and feelings. Engage in activities that you find relaxing.\n* Avoid listening to rumors that make you uncomfortable.\n\n==Long term consequences of COVID-19 pandemic on mental health==\nAccording to the Inter-Agency Standing Committee Guidelines on Mental Health and Psychosocial Support (IASC), there can be long term consequences due to the coronavirus pandemic. Deterioration of social networks and economies, stigma towards survivors of COVID-19, possible higher anger and aggression of frontline workers and the government, possible anger and aggression against children and possible mistrust of information provided by official authorities are some of the long term consequences anticipated by the IASC.<ref name= iascg/> Some of these consequences could be due to realistic dangers, but many reactions could be borne out of lack of knowledge, rumors and misinformation. It is also possible that some people may have positive experiences, such as pride about finding ways of coping. It is likely that community members show [[altruism]] and cooperation when faced with a crisis, and people might experience satisfaction from helping others.\n==Reports of mental health issues==\n* The state finance minister of Hesse, Germany, committed suicide possibly due to the mental stress from having to deal with the [[Financial_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|financial consequences of COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Welle (www.dw.com) |first1=Deutsche |title=German state finance minister Thomas Sch\u00e4fer found dead {{!}} DW {{!}} 29.03.2020 |url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-state-finance-minister-thomas-sch%C3%A4fer-found-dead/a-52948976 |work=DW.COM}}</ref>\n* There are reports of people committing suicide after not being able to access alcohol during the [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|lockdown associated with coronavirus pandemic in India]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two tipplers in Kerala commit suicide upset at not getting liquor during COVID-19 lockdown |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2020/mar/29/two-tipplers-in-kerala-commit-suicide-upset-at-not-getting-liquor-during-covid-19-lockdown-2123056.html |work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Mental health]]\n", "name_user": "Nicholas0", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spacing, hyphenation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mental_health_during_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
